<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 91 / The Blue Arrow Trial: Auditor denies trying to shield firm
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN AUDITOR who advised NatWest Investment Bank over the accounting treatment
of its Blue Arrow holdings taken in the 1987 rights issue yesterday denied
to the Blue Arrow trial that his explanation of events was an attempt to
protect his firm.
Mr Paul McNamara, a partner with Ernst &amp; Young, rejected a suggestion from
Mr Jeremy Roberts, QC, that, in an account to Sir Philip Wilkinson, the
NatWest deputy chairman, he had not told all he had known of the holdings.
Mr McNamara, Mr Roberts said, had told Sir Philip in April 1988 that Mr
James Riddell, County's finance director, had informed him the previous
November of the holdings taken by County, County NatWest Securities and
Phillips &amp; Drew. He had told Sir Philip that he had been given no details
about the transaction, Mr Roberts added, but he had been told the size of
the holdings. Mr McNamara denied that.
Mr Roberts was representing Mr Jonathan Cohen, a former County NatWest chief
executive and one of the defendants. He suggested that Mr McNamara's account
was an attempt to 'cover the backside' of his firm, then called Ernst &amp;
Whinney. Mr McNamara rejected this, saying his firm had acted with the
'highest possible standards'.
Under cross-examination by Mr Roy Amlot, QC, for Mr Alan Keat, a solicitor
who advised County over the issue, Mr McNamara later agreed he had known the
stake held by County's corporate advisory department was worth Pounds 60m.
However, nobody at Ernst &amp; Whinney had calculated from that figure what
proportion of Blue Arrow's share capital it represented, Mr McNamara said.
County NatWest, NatWest Investment Bank, UBS Phillips &amp; Drew Securities and
seven individuals all deny conspiring to mislead the markets over the
outcome of the Pounds 837m issue.
The trial continues today.
</TEXT>
