<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 91 / Most pupils opt to stay on in education
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A MAJORITY of 16-year-olds is, for the first time, staying on at school or
college rather than opting for a job or government training scheme.
Last year those staying in education rose to 53 per cent from 48 per cent in
1989, according to figures on 500,000 pupils collected by local careers
officers throughout the UK. More than three quarters of 16-year-olds now
continue either in education or on Youth Training schemes, according to the
survey, issued by the Associations of County Councils and Metropolitan
Authorities.
Local education authorities said yesterday that Britain was now beginning to
compare well with other countries in the education and training of young
people.
Mr Roy Slade, who compiled and edited the report, said the figures also
contradicted the picture painted by the Prince of Wales earlier this week
when he said that only a third of 16-year-olds remained in further
education.
The trend towards staying on in the classroom in preference to getting a job
or taking up Youth Training was reported in each of 11 regions and could not
be linked solely to the recession or the rise in unemployment, the education
authorities said.
Overall, the national figures have to be seen in the context of falling
school rolls and an overall reduction of 7.5 per cent in the year group last
year. The reduction is part of longer-term demographic shifts and the
reduction in the number of school leavers which is causing many
organisations to revise their employment policies.
Mr Kenneth Clarke, education secretary, said the figures confirmed that more
young people were recognising the importance of continuing their education
beyond the age of 16.
'The reality which these figures, and indeed our own, show is very different
from the gloomy pictures we keep hearing about,' he said. Schools that have
opted out of local-authority control will no longer have to wait five years
before changing their status, Mr Clarke announced yesterday. He said he
would consider each application on its merits.
School Leavers' Destinations 1991. ACC Publications, Eaton House, 66a Eaton
Square, London SW1W 9BH. Pounds 5.
More young people seek job or YT place, Page 14
</TEXT>
