FT  26 APR 91 / Brazil ruling on assets freeze
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTINA LAMB
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   RIO DE JANEIRO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Brazilian government has won an important legal reprieve with a decision
by the Supreme Court last night to suspend regional court rulings to
liberate money seized in a national assets freeze 13 months ago, writes
Christina Lamb in Rio de Janeiro.
The freeze is seen by the government as a crucial part of its anti-inflation
programme.
Apparently heeding dire government warnings that a release of the Dollars
27bn still frozen would cause an explosion in the inflation rate, the
president of the Supreme Court said to free the money could 'damage the
government's economic policy and provoke economic chaos.'
Yesterday's ruling came in response to a government appeal against a
decision by the court in Sao Paulo.
