<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 91 / Public spending faces squeeze: Budget targets threatened by
rise in jobless and high pay deals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MORE THAN half of the Treasury's Pounds 3bn public spending contingency
reserve has been wiped out within just three weeks of the start of the
current financial year because of rising unemployment and high public sector
pay deals.
The trend has prompted warnings in Whitehall that the depth of the recession
threatens a significant overshoot in the Pounds 8bn government deficit
forecast by Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, in his March Budget.
The economy continued to dominate Westminster yesterday with Mr Neil
Kinnock, the Labour leader, citing a report by an all-party committee of MPs
which accused the government of reacting too slowly to the recession.
'Britain's condition is very directly a result of your policies,' he told Mr
John Major, the prime minister. 'Why don't you accept responsibility or,
better still, take action to reverse this recession?'
Mr Major insisted that falling inflation and interest rates signalled an
early recovery, but it is acknowledged privately that the government may be
dogged in the immediate future by rising unemployment totals.
Senior ministers are concerned that key public spending programmes, notably
health and education, face a financial squeeze just as the government is
pledging an improvement in services in the run-up to the general election.
The Treasury has signalled the start of negotiations covering next year's
spending with a lengthy warning to every Whitehall department that it will
be seeking considerable savings elsewhere to offset the cost of higher
unemployment.
The Pounds 205bn spending target for the 1991-92 financial year, which
started on April 1, includes a Pounds 3bn reserve for unforeseen
expenditure. But unemployment is already more than 300,000 higher than the
1.75m assumed when the target was set. Even if there were no further
increase, the cost to the reserve in higher unemployment and other benefits
is about Pounds 1bn.
Another Pounds 320m of the reserve has been set aside to meet the cost of
higher-than-expected deals in the health service and the armed forces. Pay
deals in other areas of the public sector have been averaging 8 per cent,
well above assumptions.
The Treasury has acknowledged that its decision to raise child benefit will
cost Pounds 220m from the reserve, while the Department of Employment has
been allocated an extra Pounds 120m for training.
Ironically, the Budget decision to raise VAT to 17.5 per cent will cost
Whitehall departments some Pounds 450m. Mr William Waldegrave, the health
secretary, has secured agreement from the Treasury that the extra burden on
the NHS will be met from the reserve.
Overall, the demands mean that half of the reserve has been spent, and about
two-thirds of the Pounds 3bn which was notionally available three weeks ago
has been pre-empted. Another rise in unemployment could account for the
rest, since even the more optimistic forecasts point to a further 250,000
increase this year.
The outlook for next year - for which spending departments will submit their
bids by mid-May - is similarly bleak. In theory the Treasury has a Pounds
7bn reserve for 1992-93, but the increases this year will pre-empt half of
that.
Inflation will be sharply lower by next year, but that assumption is built
into budgets for 1992-93. The allocations for the NHS and education, in
particular, allow for only minimal real growth next year, suggesting the two
departments will seek several billion pounds more from the Treasury.
Meanwhile, Mr Michael Heseltine, the environment secretary, is expected to
need at least Pounds 1.5bn in extra grants for local authorities to cushion
the impact of the poll tax in what he has promised will be its final year.
The new demands could wipe out the scope for tax cuts and force the Treasury
to revise upwards what many in the City see as an over-optimistic view of
the likely trend in public borrowing.
Kinnock rejects Major's optimism Page 13
All-party warning on depth of recession Page 24
</TEXT>
