<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 91 / Recession fears put pressure on pound
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RACHEL JOHNSON, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
STERLING came under selling pressure early yesterday as investors took
profits in case the currency should succumb to the strong dollar and
domestic worries.
A big sell order from the Middle East and growing concern that the UK
recession is lengthening conspired to push the pound briefly from third to
ninth place in the European exchange rate mechanism grid.
Up to yesterday, the pound had been resilient in the face of the dollar's
surge on the foreign exchanges. The pronounced weakness of the D-Mark
enabled sterling to hold its position in the ERM.
In the latest session in London, however, the pound was driven to a low of
DM2.9488 - against its previous close of DM2.9725 - before finishing 1.25
pfennigs off on the day at DM2.96, back in its place as third strongest
currency in the ERM. It closed almost unchanged against the dollar at
Dollars 1.694. Later in New York, it closed at Dollars 1.691 and DM2.9575.
Rumours that the Bank of England had stepped in to support the pound were
treated with scepticism by traders.
Mr Paul Chertkow, currency strategist at Citibank, the US bank, said the
pound had mainly suffered as a result of technical profit-taking yesterday.
But growing evidence that the UK economic recovery would not come as soon or
be as strong as forecast also undermined the pound.
This week's claim by the director general of the Confederation of British
Industry that some parts of UK manufacturing were in 'slump' came after the
government had announced record rises in unemployment and large falls in
industrial output. The news prompted renewed calls for lower interest rates
to stimulate the economy.
However, the government has said there must be a 'pause' in its efforts to
lower borrowing costs to allow sterling to settle down after the bank base
rate had been cut to 12 per cent from 14 per cent in mid-February.
A political risk has also attached to sterling ahead of the May 2 local
elections. Should the Conservative Party do badly, traders expect sterling
to fall below its DM2.95 central ERM rate.
US presses for rate cut, Page 8
Money Markets, Page 39
