<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 91 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (40): A new channel
for grievances - Pensions / But the Ombudsman's influence does have limits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ERIC SHORT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EMPLOYEES and their dependents, who have a grievance about their pensions or
other benefits from their company pension scheme, can now have their
complaint investigated by the Pensions Ombudsman, Michael Platt.
He opened his doors for business at the beginning of this month, operating
from an office* in London.
The Occupational Pensions Advisory Service (Opas), under the guidance of its
founder, Margaret Grainger, has provided a very successful voluntary
complaints service for the past seven years. But it had no legal teeth, and
had to rely on tact and persuasion.
If this failed, the only recourse open to a person with a pension grievance,
and who could get no redress from a company scheme or an employer, was
through the courts - a time-consuming and often prohibitively expensive
exercise. The Pension Ombudsman, set up under the 1990 Social Security Act,
provides a free, user-friendly service. He has wide statutory powers to
investigate and settle disputes.
The government's original intention was that the ombudsman would handle all
complaints relating to private-sector pensions, including personal pensions;
but subsequent regulations have required it to draw back from this
all-embracing concept. Nevertheless, he still has very wide powers. He can
adjudicate on complaints about injustice caused by maladministration, and in
a dispute of fact or law.
A clearer idea of how Mr Platt is developing his role will emerge when he
makes his first annual report. Nevertheless, any individual with a grievance
over pensions should not stop to consider whether or not it falls within the
Ombudsman's reference, but contact the bureau.
The ombudsman cannot usurp the functions of the trustees in exercising their
discretions, such as the payment of a death-in-service benefit; but he can
ensure that the trustees have operated within the rules of the scheme, and
that they have taken all relevant facts into consideration.
Again, the ombudsman cannot directly overrule the scheme actuary in the
calculation of transfer values. But he can ensure that the actuary has
conformed to the professional guidelines in making the calculation, and that
the basic details, such as length of service, are correct.
The ombudsman has adopted the policy long followed by Opas, that no one
making a complaint will get a purely negative response. If he cannot deal
with the complaint, then advice and guidance will be given as to whether
another complaints body might handle it; or, failing that, the complainant
may be given an explanation of his situation. For the ombudsman has
incorporated Opas into his operations, to handle the advisory and
conciliatory aspects of the service.
The stages of handling a complaint are:
1, The complainant must first raise the matter with the trustees or managers
of the scheme.
2, If he or she fails to get satisfaction, then he should contact Opas for
help. If the complainant contacts Opas without having first raised the
matter with the trustees or managers, Opas would tell him to do so, though
would also give guidance on who to approach and how to raise the matter.
This service is useful to a person who has a complaint or enquiry about
benefits from a previous employer's scheme with whom he has had no dealings
for some time.
3, Opas, through its countrywide team of voluntary advisers, would examine
and investigate the complaint. Most of the complaints so far received by
Opas arose through misunderstanding on the part of the complainant, or
maladministration by the scheme, and can be resolved by explanation or
negotiation. The complainant can go direct to the ombudsman, but the
ombudsman will encourage him to go to Opas first.
4, Where Opas is not able to resolve the complaint, either through
unwillingness on the part of the scheme trustees or the complainant, or
because adjudication is required, then the Ombudsman will investigate the
complaint. He has the statutory powers to require schemes to produce
documents, explain their attitudes and decisions and attend hearings. He can
seek the guidance of the courts on points of law.
Above all, his decision is binding on both the scheme and the complainant,
subject to appeal on a point of law.
Michael Platt hopes it will be possible to handle most cases by letter. But
where necessary, he will have personal hearings, either separately with both
parties, or jointly with both present. Complaints must be made within three
years of the matter's arising, though this can be extended if the facts were
not known within the time, or if it was not practicable to complain within
the time-limit.
The ombudsman can deal only with individual complaints; so where there is a
general complaint, such as occurred recently with the pensioners in the
Imperial Tobacco pension scheme, a person must be selected to make a
test-case complaint. Complainants can be legally represented, and the
Ombudsman has the power to award costs. But since this is not a tribunal, a
complainant cannot apply for legal aid.
*The address of both the Pensions Ombudsman and the Occupational Pensions
Advisory Service is 11, Belgrave Road, London SW1V 1RB. But there are
separate telephone numbers: the Ombudsman is 071 834-9144, and Opas 071
233-8080.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XXXIII Photograph Michael Platt ...individuals only (Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-2980</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BDZA8AFKFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910426
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 91 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (39): The middle
class looks beyond manana - Other people's money / Democracy has changed
Spanish people's attitudes towards savings
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER BRUCE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
JUAN JOSE Suarez, a 43-year-old journalist and broadcaster in Madrid has,
for a Spaniard, an almost unique problem. 'I am over-insured,' he complains.
'I have policies with Mapfre, with Winterthur, with Barclays Bank, with New
York Life.'
He also has two mortgages, a new car, three children and a charming American
wife, Susan, of whose expensive decorating tastes he will occasionally
complain, only to be instantly put in his place if he has failed to complain
out of earshot.
Juan Jose has no idea how much the family purse haemorrhages a month in
insurance premiums for the two houses, the cars and the multiple life
policies, but he is beginning to show signs of resistance. It was Susan,
drawing on her Anglo-Saxon upbringing, who sold him on the idea of putting
something away for the future.
'Our Spanish culture was very fatalistic,' he reminds enquirers, 'the
natural enemy of insurance and prudence.'
That childhood legacy probably still tears at him a little, though he
acknowleges that, now that he and other middle-class Spaniards have become
quite seriously wealthy, the sense that one should protect what one has has
grown strong.
'We went very quickly from nothing to everything,' says Juan Jose. 'Now we
worry about losing it. We worry about the durability and strength of the
social-security system. I'm going to live a long time, and I know that
spending money on insurance policies is not throwing it away.'
The lack of provision made by a society that is rightly praised for its
verve and zest for life meant that, by the time General Francisco Franco's
protective and paternalistic 39-year dictatorship came to an end in 1975,
Spain's savings rate was very low (statistically, it is traditionally high,
but savings accounts are subject to quick turnover) and practically no
attempt was being made, beyond the banking and savings bank networks, to
attract saving.
Low savings are still a problem for the Spanish economy, making it rely too
heavily on the entry of foreign capital to finance its deficits. But,
inevitably, the existence of a virgin market of 35m people was not going to
be left alone for long. From the moment the democratic authorities began
allowing foreign banks into the country, at the end of the 1970s, Spanish
habits began, slowly, to change.
Life insurance was a particularly stubborn nut to crack, and it was only
when insurers began to market the fiscal advantages of their policies -
rather than the Anglo-Saxon notion of preparing for old age or unexpected
death - that people began to take notice. Still, by 1986, the industry had
managed to sell only 2.1m policies to a probably small stratum of people who
had enough money to actually worry about how to avoid paying taxes. In
contrast, the mainstay of the insurance industry, car insurance, accounted
for nearly 12m policies.
That picture has changed in the past four years. Car insurance has become
increasingly unprofitable as Spain's crammed roads and impatient drivers
cause more and more accidents. But the rush of foreign entrants into the
market, smothering the television and newspaper advertising markets with
life policies and pension plans, and quickly copied by local institutions,
has bulldozed its way through fatalism, disbelief and suspicion.
By the end of 1989, the number of life polices had more than doubled to
4.4m. Car insurance, meanwhile, had grown just 16 per cent to 14.8m
policies. Where Spaniards were spending just Pta 11,000 a head on insurance
at the beginning of the 1980s, they were spending Pta 60,000 (Pounds 330) by
the end of the decade.
At the same time, a vicious battle was being waged between foreign and local
banks, and local savings banks, to attract and, more important, hold on to
savers. In late 1989, local banks finally laid their old interest-rate
cartel to rest and began to compete directly for rich savers - offering high
interest-bearing current accounts on amounts over Pta 1m. That has been an
expensive exercise for the commercial banks, and the big savings banks are
only beginning to compete, having first been forced to leave the insurance
market.
But while the growth of services and automation in Spanish banking has been
spectacular (one savings bank is working on machines that would enable
people to buy and sell shares), the most telling measure of change has been
the quick growth of personal-pension funds since the government first
allowed them to operate at the beginning of 1990.
In their first year, about 150 new pension-fund managers were able to
generate Pta 85bn-worth of business, but no one dreamed they would double
that by the end of last year, to some Pta 170bn. According to Mr Jose
Miracle, the government's pension-fund supervisor, 530,000 Spaniards now
have their own pension plans. 'Its an incredible number,' he says. 'It's
clear that, in this country, a certain layer of people have come to regard
long-term savings as an absolutely essential cover.'
Well, sort of. Talk to the Spaniards who are buying life policies and
pension plans, and it quickly becomes clear why they are so attractive.
Alfonso Moreno, a rich young financial analyst, quickly bought into a
pension scheme. 'I did it for fiscal reasons,' he says, meaning that what he
found attractive about the schemes is that they allow contributions of Pta
500,000 to be fully deducted from income tax and that a further Pta 250,000
is 15 per cent deductable.
So what about old age and all that? 'Look,' he says, 'I'm irresponsible. I
suppose if I were married I would do it differently.'
It is probably a reflection of their professions, but Alfonso Moreno and
Juan Jose Suarez approach buying their products in very different ways.
Alfonso says that, when he wants to borrow money (he has, truly, just bought
a Porsche), he shops around. 'You can save up to two points,' he says. As
banks vie for business, Alfonso's favourite stopping-points at the moment
are Barclays and the Caja de Catalunya, a Catalan savings bank.
Juan Jose says he makes a point of 'never asking about the interest rate,
just the length of time I have to pay the money back'. On the Pta 12m
mortgage he has just taken out? 'I got a good deal - 10 years  - but I don't
know what interest I'm paying and I haven't asked.'
Juan Jose is probably the more typical Spanish borrower. Which probably
explains why so many people are trying to lend him and the rest of the
country money. The sheer spread of offers at least means he is spoiled for
choice and is not going to get ripped off too badly.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XXXII Photograph A longer view, Madrilanos have begun to take
thought for the autumn of their lives (Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-2981</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BDZA8AFJFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910426
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 91 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (38): Clowns or
beauties still light up the collector - Alternative Investments / Most
cigarette cards are worth little, but a rare set may fetch a fancy price
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN AMERICAN collecting fanatic last month paid Dollars 450,000 (Pounds
254,000) for a cigarette card.
But don't bother ransacking the attic for that old box containing the cards
of your childhood. This was the one-off price needed to acquire the most
perfect example of the rarest and most desirable card in the market.
It is a portrait of the baseball player Honus Wagner, a big name around
1910. Wagner was an ardent anti-smoker, and when he discovered that his
likeness was being used to promote sales of cigarettes he asked the tobacco
company to withdraw the card. Fewer than 40 Wagner cards are known to have
survived, and less than 10 are in good condition. This one is the finest:
hence the price.
Most cigarette cards are virtually worthless. They were produced in their
billions in the UK and the US from the 1880s up to the second world war. But
they have always been collected, first by small boys, and now mainly by
middle aged men, nostalgic about their youth. (For some reason they have
minimal appeal to women). And the rarer sets, especially those of the
pre-1920 period, go for fancy prices: the British record is the Pounds
17,050 paid at Phillips in 1987 for a set of 20 Taddy's Clowns.
This was quite exceptional. Two rich collectors had been trying for years to
acquire these rare cards, of which only 15 complete sets are known, for
their holdings and they chased each other up in the saleroom. If a set of
Taddy's Clowns appeared on the market now, it would probably go for around
Pounds 7,000 - the underbidder on the record price was soon able to complete
his set, reducing the demand.
The same fanaticism fuels the search for cards from an even rarer set,
'Tobacco Leaf Girls', Edwardian beauties who have maintained their appeal.
One card could make Pounds 800; perhaps much more if two collectors need it
to complete the set of 20. The highest prices tend to be paid for the
earliest cards, such as 'Pirates', by the American manufacturers Allen &amp;
Ginter in 1888 and valued at over Pounds 300 a set. The only post-1930 set
to attract exceptional prices is the 'Life of Edward VIII', which
disappeared from the streets as quickly as the monarch. A set might cost
Pounds 1,500.
Around 15,000 sets of cards were issued in the UK. By the 1920s, Wills and
Players had bought out most of the smaller cigarette makers, like Taddy,
Kinnear, Duke &amp; Sons, Richmond Cavendish and Salmon &amp; Gluckstein; and for
almost two decades were pumping out annually new sets by the hundred.
Today, they can usually be bought for around Pounds 10 a set, with really
popular subjects, like the Kings and Queens of England, produced in massive
quantities in the 1930s, worth now around Pounds 5 - less if the cards are
stuck in one of the books published by the tobacco companies to encourage
loyalty to the brand. Serious collectors place their cards in protective
plastic covers. As well as rarity, condition is all-important: creased or
dog eared cards have minimal appeal.
The low value of most cards means that, these days, the auction houses tend
to sell them in vast job-lots - if they sell them at all. Phillips still
includes cigarette cards in its sales of books or collectables at its rooms
in Leeds, Ipswich, and Sherborne, as well as at London West Two. Christie's
South Kensington now has two substantial sales a year and confines
appropriate cigarette cards to specialist auctions - on such subjects as
cricket, fishing and aviation.
Generally, a saleroom lot which contains a few rare cards and carries an
estimate of up to Pounds 100 sells at around its target. The lots containing
thousands of popular cards from mixed sets, and with estimates up to Pounds
300, sometimes make much more as dealers compete for the hoard. These cards
will then be matched into sets and retailed at collector's fairs or street
antique stalls with a substantial mark-up.
There are specialist dealers who tend to offer a postal service. They can be
tracked down through the periodical Card Times. But around 70 per cent of
the lots at auction go to private buyers, who might do some weekend trading
of their spares to finance their hobby.
Christie's South Kensington noticed that prices in its October 18 sale were
appreciably higher than in the spring of 1990 when demand was weak: perhaps
the cutback in the number of auctions had left the dealers short of stock.
This would account for a job-lot of 129 complete sets, including many
pre-1920, selling for Pounds 4,620, as against a top estimate of Pounds 500.
A Phillips auction in Leeds, in late February, also suggested a healthy
market. One lot, consisting of cards from FJ Smith's 'Cricketers' - as well
as 'War Incidents (First Series)' and 'British Butterflies', from Godfrey
Phillips - made Pounds 297, against a top estimate of Pounds 50. Twenty-four
full sets of natural history and sport, conservatively estimated at up to
Pounds 100, went for Pounds 407. It does not matter too much if a set is not
complete - it is usually possible to acquire from a dealer the missing
cards.
But it is hard to predict price frenzy among the cigarette cards. The
collectors are getting older; the likely frequency of rare cards appearing
for sale is known; price levels have moved in line with inflation, but no
more. Certain areas are perenially attractive to collectors, like cards of
cricketers, which have shown an impressive rise in value in the past decade.
This has now levelled off. Boxers seem currently to be attracting attention,
joining Edwardian beauties as bankable propositions. Anyone with a little
surplus income could form an impressive cigarette card collection quite
quickly and painlessly.
But this misses the point. The attraction for enthusiasts lies in slowly
assembling sets in a particular area - sporting cards, military cards,
pre-1910 cards, cards produced by lesser-known cigarette-makers - and
pouring over the inevitable card stall at a boot-sale or at a Sunday morning
gathering of like-minded collectors, trading and exchanging until the
holding is complete.
Few areas offer the thrill of the chase with quite so many possibilities of
success. And there is undoubted investment potential among the earlier,
rarer, cards.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
