<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 91 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (37): Keeping the
house in order - On the move / Managers' careers may also interest savers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CERI JONES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE IS particular reason this year to ensure that the fund manager
investing your money has a long and steady record, and as much experience as
possible of volatile markets.
Yet while the expertise of the individual managing the fund is fundamental,
there is no real mystique about the investment business - the management
principles are much the same as for any other industry.
Paul Haines, investment director of consulting actuary Noble Lowndes, says:
'There have been no career changes in the last six months where people who
have moved are so good that they could change my perception of an investment
house overnight. But some could change the house over a period of time.
Sometimes the problem with a house is not the quality of the staff, but the
way the house is managed. If there was a house where the investment
philosophy is sound but the management is poor, then a good leader can
provide what the house is lacking.'
Mr Haines also questioned the widely-held assumption that an investment
group necessarily suffers when a brilliant and charismatic manager leaves.
'If a manager is really exceptional, then he will train people in his
culture and that culture may persist beyond his own physical presence.'
There are, however, two typical scenarios that are likely to take their toll
on a group's fund performance.
The first is where a group's traditional fund management department falls
under the general business function, so that fund managers are remunerated
on the same scale as managers in other departments. The best fund managers
in their field can demand far more than such a structure allows. This type
of structural problem occurs most frequently in insurance companies. The
second is where different parts of a group are being merged, either through
corporate takeover or the internal rationalisation of one company - for
example, the merger of a group's pension and unit-trust arms.
That said, the appointment of one exceptional manager can boost client
confidence in a group, which in turn works like a self-fulfilling prophesy.
An example might be the former chief of Prudential Portfolio Managers, Giles
Weaver, who returned to his native Scotland in October to take up a
directorship at Murray Johnstone, with overall responsibility for UK
investment and pensions. Murray Johnstone has had mixed fortunes over the
last 12 months. Funds under management fell by Pounds 700m in 1990; its
attempts at merger have so far proved fruitless; and last month it
streamlined its operation with the redundancy of a further 20 staff.
However, the company claims it has not lost a single client since Mr
Weaver's appointment.
Hill Samuel Investment Services (HSIS) has also experienced a bumpy 12
months. Last month, chief executive Derek Fitch took early retirement
following the group's decision to restructure the company into two parts.
One arm is now headed by John Penny and concentrates on life, pensions and
mortgage business; the other is led by John Bourke, and deals with private
client services and offshore operations. One of the biggest blows to the
group was the departure in December of David Tilles and his team of four,
who had managed the Marks &amp; Spencer UK Selection Portfolio unit trust. They
left to form Delaware International Advisers, taking the Pounds 13.5m M&amp;S
contract with them.
This also followed the departure of HSIS former managing director David
Barker, who left in February 1990 to join Royal Insurance Asset Management
as managing director, with the brief to oversee all of royal's
fund-management functions.
Another troubled house, Kleinwort Benson, appointed Charles Cavanagh last
month as director and head of UK institutional fund management. Mr Cavanagh
was previously responsible for client relationships with UK pension funds at
Mercury Asset Management.
Not all moves are from one house to another. In January, Kleinwort Benson's
colourful Japanese unit trust manager, Campbell Gunn, moved to Switzerland
to manage private client funds from the company's Geneva office. His
position has been filled by Mark Pearson, who also managed the Kleinwort
Benson Japanese Specialist trust and had worked alongside his predecessor
for three years.
Other significant recent job-changes of note in the fund-management
fraternity include Jimmy West's move to Lazards as chief executive in
December, following the takeover of Globe Investment Trust by the Coal Board
Pension Fund.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XXX
