<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 91 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (34): The industry
needs small investors - Marketing / But seeking them through independent
financial advisers will mean paying the same sort of commission levels that
unit trusts have paid in the past - Investment trusts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARRY RILEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FOR FAR too long investment-trust companies assumed that investment trusts
would sell themselves. After all, they were plainly such an attractive
investment, when compared with say unit trusts, that savers would surely
come knocking at the door.
But they didn't. Over the decades the private investors in many investment
trusts died, or at any rate sold their shares, and the shares drifted to
wider and wider discounts against underlying assets. During the early 1980s
the average discount regularly came close to 30 per cent.
As prices drifted, investment institutions such as life-insurance companies
and pension funds came in to mop up the investment-trust shares. Usually
they did not regard them as appropriate investments, but at a low enough
price they were worth tucking away in institutional portfolios.
In this way, the big funds often came to own 70 per cent of an investment
trust's shares. This is the topsy-turvy situation in which the boards of
many trusts find themselves, and they know that such trusts have little
future unless the balance is redressed. The takeover of the giant Globe
Investment Trust last year, to be broken up by the pension funds of British
Coal, was yet another ghastly warning, if another were needed.
Now, nearly all the investment-trust managements accept that more effective
marketing to personal investors is essential if the investment trust
industry is to survive in anything like its present form.
In the distant past, investment trusts were able to rely on stockbrokers to
market their products. The reward of the brokers was the commission on the
deal, nowadays of something like 1.7 per cent on small bargains (it used to
be rather less). But stockbrokers have in many cases tended to become less
interested in private clients. Alternatively, they have sold unit trusts on
a significantly bigger 3 per cent commission.
Meanwhile, larger and larger proportions of the long-term savings of the
public over the years have gone into life insurance contracts and personal
pensions, sold by intermediaries who receive even more lucrative
commissions.
Such products can be sold aggressively through advertising or through
mail-order shots, and even through 'cold calls' on a door-to-door or
telephone sales basis. These rules have applied for many years now.
Investment trust shares, on the other hand, have come under the tight
restrictions which apply to the promotion of company shares in general, and
are designed to curb the activities of unscrupulous share pushers and
'boiler room' telephone selling operators.
But now big changes are in the offing. The Securities and Investments Board,
the top watchdog body for investments, has decided that investment trusts
should be put more in line with alternative savings products. Investment
trust savings schemes, at least, will soon be much more freely marketable to
the public. The new regulations may come into force later this year.
So far, investment-trust savings schemes have had to skate around the
existing rules. Investment trusts have not been permitted to sell 'off the
page' using coupons, as unit trusts can. Rather, investment-trust management
companies have had to advertise brochures, which is selling at one remove.
Still, investment-trust savings schemes pulled in Pounds 91m during 1990, a
42 per cent increase on the 1990 figure, despite poor market conditions.
Moreover, investment trusts have already been given a role in personal
equity plans. They are on a par with unit trusts in this tax privilege,
which gives both of them something of an advantage over life insurance
products. The latest Budget changes will serve to widen the range of
investment trusts which can qualify for Pounds 3,000 peps.
Now, the investment-trust marketing men are gearing up to take on the rival
savings media more directly. More and more, they are seeking to reach the
public through independent financial advisers, the sort of intermediaries
who sell life policies, pension plans and unit trusts. The trade body, the
AITC, has just hired a marketing executive with a brief to help member
investment trust companies to reach such intermediaries.
However, this means paying the same sort of commission levels - usually 3
per cent of a lump sum investment - that unit trusts have paid in the past.
Thus there are pluses and minuses in all this for the investor. Investment
trusts are starting to offer rather worse value for money, but on the other
hand the discount on assets is shrinking, which is very good for existing
investors and offers the promise of reduced share price volatility to future
investors too.
A further step has been taken by Foreign &amp; Colonial, now the biggest
investment trust. In a pioneering deal with Skandia Life, its shares are
being used as the investment medium for life insurance and personal pensions
products.
There is still, however, something like Pounds 15bn of funds of
institutional investors in the investment-trust market. If that pool of
capital is to be replaced by private investors' money within a reasonably
short period of time, the investment trusts' new marketing men are going to
have to work very hard.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XXVIII Photograph Their pension funds' break-up of Globe last
year provided another warning (Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-2986</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BDZA8AFEFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910426
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 91 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (33): The yield is
handy, but watch the parabola - Split-capital trusts / A 1960s golden oldie
may appeal to seekers of both income and of capital growth - Investment
trusts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE SPLIT-capital trust is definitely in vogue. Every other new
investment-trust issue seems to have several different classes of shares,
and such trusts now make up 10 per cent of the sector.
The main reason for the revival - the previous heyday of split capital
trusts was in the 1960s - is the ability of managers to structure the trusts
in ways that make them attractive to private investors. Income shares, in
particular, appeal to the older investor. Allied to a personal equity plan
(Pep), such trusts can provide vital tax-free income.
Some trust managers have been able to exploit an element of the Pep rules,
which allows new issues to be transferred, without charge, into a plan
within 42 days of the first day of dealings.
The rules allow investors to put the full Pounds 6,000 into a new issue Pep,
rather than the normal investment-trust limit of Pounds 3,000. Indeed,
trusts launched at the end of last tax year allowed investors to place as
much as Pounds 12,000 into two Peps, one for the 1990-91 fiscal year and one
for 1991-92.
One interesting variant of the income shares was created in the recent
launch of the Contra-Cyclical Investment Trust, managed by Rea Brothers. The
income shares will pay a very high initial yield, but will only be repaid a
penny in the pound when the trust is wound up in 10 years' time.
The Contra-Cyclical share thus resembles a temporary annuity - with the
advantage that, if the investor dies, his estate will still be able to sell
the shares at the market price. With an annuity, death means the loss of the
entire investment.
The price of most income shares follows a parabola - rising above asset
value in the first few years, and then falling back to par as the wind-up of
the trust approaches. This can make them dangerous investments for the
unwary, who may be attracted by the yield when the price is high, without
realising they will face a capital loss. However, this quirk can be used to
advantage by investors with a large capital gains tax liability. They can
buy income shares at the peak price and create an offsetting capital loss,
while enjoying the income.
Income is not the only advantage that a split-capital trust can offer the
private investor. If all the income is being siphoned off to one class of
investor, that leaves all the capital growth to the rest.
One class of shares that has become particularly popular in the recent
revival is the zero-dividend preference share. As the name suggests, this
brings no income but will normally be first to be repaid when the trust is
wound up. Barring a disaster, repayment will be at a level which guarantees
healthy capital growth.
For the small investor who has not used up his capital gains tax allowance,
these shares offer an attractive tax-free gain. And even investors who have
already used up their Pounds 5,500 CGT limit can use the shares to make
tax-free gains via a Pep.
Those willing to take larger risks may be interested in the capital shares
of split trusts. These promise substantial gains if stock markets, and the
managers of the trust, perform well.
Capital shares are highly risky. The normal split-capital trust structure
means that the capital shares will be worthless unless the assets of the
trust grow - and sometimes they need to grow substantially. But modest
growth rates in assets - of, say, 7.5 to 10 per cent per annum - can often
mean a substantial multiple of the share price.
Different trusts use different combinations of these shares, but they
normally revolve around the three basics - income, assured capital growth
and risky capital growth.
The attraction of these share varieties has created substantial demand, with
the result that many of the trusts trade at a premium to their net asset
value. 'I think the sector will grow, because of demand not only from
private investors, but also from institutional clients who want an income
stream,' says Lewis Aaron, an analyst at Barclays de Zoete Wedd.
Mr Aaron expects more trust launches, particularly towards the end of the
tax year, and more restructuring of existing trusts into split-capital form,
with the aim of attracting institutional interest.
However, the continued health of the sector depends on demand being
maintained and not swamped by oversupply. It may also depend on the stock
markets performing well enough to prevent any disasters, such as capital
shareholders recording a total loss.
If disasters are avoided, and the managers show continuing creativity in
inventing new classes of shares with investor appeal, then the split-capital
sector is likely to be an important factor in propelling the investment
industry into the next millennium.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
