<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 91 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (28): Long-distance
pacesetters - Performance / Last year was gloomy, but the horizon offers
encouragement - Investment trusts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PERFORMANCE of investment trusts in 1990 offers a salutary lesson to
investors: that the search for short-term profit may end with fool's gold.
Average net asset values in the sector fell 25 per cent over the year -
underperforming the FT-A All-Share index by 11 per cent. Of 206 trusts
tracked by brokers County NatWest Woodmac, only 39 managed to beat the
All-Share. And only one trust in this sample, F and C Enterprise, was able
to maintain its share price over the 12-month period. Explanations for this
dismal showing are easy enough to find. The strength of the pound, which
gained significantly against most major currencies like the dollar, the yen
and the Deutsche Mark, hit the value of trusts' overseas assets on
translation into sterling.
The relatively poor performance of overseas indices, meanwhile (notably
those of Japan and other Pacific Basin countries), inevitably prejudiced the
returns of investment vehicles which had 50 per cent of their assets
overseas at the start of last year.
Looking at performance over a longer time-frame restores the morale of fund
managers, and provides the main justification for investment in investment
trusts. Figures from the Association of Investment Trust Companies (AITC)
indicate that the sector as a whole has shown banks and building societies a
clean pair of heels, looked its unit-trust rivals squarely in the eye, and
generally kept pace with the UK stock market as measured by the All-Share
index.
On average, for example, a Pounds 100 investment in a UK general investment
trust grew to Pounds 175 in the five years to last December, or almost
Pounds 475 over the 10-year period to end-1990. Leaving the money in a
building society over these periods would have left the investor with just
Pounds 155 and Pounds 239 respectively, while he would have been even worse
off in a bank deposit account.
The AITC monthly figures (available from financial advisers, stockbrokers,
or direct from the Association) are the best source of comparative
performance statistics. Two main yardsticks are used - share-price total
return, and net-asset-value total return, which in each case is a measure of
the combined performance of the capital growth and income.
The share price is what investors pay for their shares in the market. The
NAV is the current value of the assets backing each ordinary share issued by
an investment trust: it comes after deduction of all the liabilities due to
creditors, and all capital with a claim to repayment ahead of ordinary
shareholders.
Movements in net asset values are useful, because they arguably show more
accurately than share prices the skill, or otherwise, of the investment
manager. Share prices, on the other hand, represent the actual value of an
investment to the shareholder in the market, and may therefore be deemed a
more appropriate guide.
The difference between the share price and net asset value is known as
either the discount or the premium. At their simplest, these are a
reflection of the imbalance between supply and demand for investment-trust
shares, and can have a major impact on performance.
Last year, for example, a 4 per cent premium for trusts investing in the
emerging markets of Asia had turned into a 17 per cent discount at the end
of last year as investor enthusiasm waned. This year, by contrast, has seen
a revival of interest in small companies, and investment trusts have been
identified as a means of buying exposure to the sector. Trusts like TR
Smaller Companies have seen their discount narrow, while Kleinwort Smaller
Companies and Aberforth Trust shares have both been on a premium in recent
weeks.
It cannot be said often enough that past performance is not necessarily a
guide to the future. One-year figures, although keenly watched by investment
managers themselves and publicised in the press, are less reliable than
five- and 10-year statistics when it comes to gauging a trust's consistency.
Certainly, trusts with general investment objectives can be usefully judged
in this way, though the potential for takeover or re-rating in a high
discount should not be overlooked when it comes to making a choice.
Apart from looking at performance in isolation, it is as well to put trust
records into perspective. The normal yardstick is the FT-A All-Share index,
which reflects how the UK stock market as a whole has behaved. The advantage
of this is that it is well understood by the majority of investors. The
drawback is that, with many trusts largely or even wholly invested outside
the UK, it is not a particularly fair or meaningful comparison.
