<PROFILE>_AN-BDZA8AE5FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910426
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 91 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (24): Discount
became a loss - Hindsight / Even a small-print reader may trip over the
rules
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   THE INVESTMENT world is rife with traps for the unwary
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
and they are not all set by sharks or fraudsters. Even innocent transactions
can take great bites out of your investments, if you are not careful.
Hard-won investment gains have a habit of seeping away through management,
dealing and other charges.
Attention to detail and a willingness to read the small print helps. But
even that is not proof against unexpected loss.
Mr Ron Boyce, a part-retired civil engineer from Hayling Island, is a
small-print reader. He is well-informed and has a healthy degree of
scepticism when it comes to trusting other people with his money. Yet Mr
Boyce and his wife, Sheila, still managed to see a large chunk wiped off
part of their investment portfolio during what should have been a routine
investment operation.
Mrs Boyce had held unit trusts managed by Prolific for four years when she
and her husband decided to switch the investment into a personal equity plan
(Pep) in February. Yet the deal ended up wiping 8.7 per cent cent off the
value of their investment, even after a special discount from Prolific.
The Boyces did not make any serious errors, and Prolific did not rip them
off. They were just the victims of what can often be costly inefficiencies
in the investment markets.
At the root of the problem is the fact that it is not possible to transfer
existing investments into Peps - they have to be sold and bought back. Also,
under Financial Services Act rules, there has to be a seven-day 'cooling
off' period after a Pep application is received, to give potential investors
a chance to change their minds. Taken together, these rules caught out the
Boyces.
Their application was received by Prolific towards the end of February, and
their units (in the company's High Income and Extra Income unit trusts) were
sold on 21st. The money was then held for seven days, before being used to
repurchase units within the Pep.
During that time, the Boyces were out of the stock market - an unfortunate
week to be in that position, as the market surged. According to figures
supplied by Prolific, this led to a 4.3 per cent rise in the unit price of
the High Income fund and 3.6 per cent for the Extra Income. Buying the units
back was therefore a lot more expensive.
A close reading of the small print in Prolific's Pep brochure does not make
this market risk altogether clear. It explains the seven-day rule. It does
not explain, though, that existing units will be sold immediately by the
company, rather than at the end of the cooling-off period, giving rise to
the market risk. Prolific has since told the Boyces that the seven-day rule
is no longer required, and that it is reconsidering its policy in this area.
Also, it says it sees nothing wrong with its literature and no reason to
change it. That accounts for part of the Boyces' 'loss'. The rest resulted
from an aspect of unit-trust pricing that, again, even the most careful
reader of the small print might not expect.
The Boyces expected to sell units at Prolific's bid price, and buy them back
at the offer price. The loss that resulted from paying the spread between
bid and offer prices would largely be recouped by a 4 per cent discount
offered by Prolific (3 per cent available to all clients who switch, and 1
per cent for taking out a Pep).
Prolific's Pep brochure gives illustrative figures for what the spread is
likely to be. At the start of this year it was 6 per cent (generally in line
with other unit trusts). The spread could get wider, though: there is a
maximum permitted spread of 8.2 per cent for the High Income unit trust, and
7.9 per cent for the Extra Income fund.
The Boyces ended up suffering virtually the biggest spreads permissible  -
8.1 per cent and 7.8 per cent respectively. Why was the spread so big?
Because, explained Prolific, of a change in the basis of pricing the units
during the week between the sale and repurchase.
There are two different ways of pricing units. The choice of method depends
on whether a unit-trust manager is selling more units to investors than he
is buying back (in which case he is creating new units), or buying back more
units than he is selling (in which case he is cancelling surplus units).
In the first case, a 'creation price' is calculated, to reflect the costs of
creating new units. This is the price at which they are offered to
investors. In such cases, a unit trust is said to be priced on an offer
basis, and the price moves towards the top end of its permitted range.
When the manager is a net buyer of units, on the other hand, it calculates a
'cancellation' price, to cover the cost of selling the underlying shares. In
such cases, the unit trust is priced on a bid basis, and the price moves to
the lower end of its range. So the pricing can change a lot, depending on
the manager's situation at any particular time.
The Boyces fell foul of this process. Between the time their units were sold
and repurchased, Prolific switched from pricing its units on a bid basis to
pricing them on an offer basis. That meant that the Boyces sold at the low
cancellation price, but had to buy back at the high creation price.
In all, these factors left the Boyces with 1,671 units in the High Income
trust (compared with the 1,793 they started with) and 1,126 in the Extra
Income trust (compared with 1,232). That equates to a capital loss of Pounds
247.96 (the pre-loss value of their investment had been Pounds 2,853).
It takes time and and care to build up investments. Such losses can take a
long time to recoup. Given the current rates of income on the Prolific unit
trusts, the switch to the Pep will save Mrs Boyce Pounds 28.63 a year in
tax. That means it will be nearly nine years before the tax savings from the
Pep more than make up for the cost of switching in the first place.
'We should have known better,' says a rueful Mr Boyce.
He had always been distrustful of Peps, aware of the high management charge
that can wipe out any tax advantages. But the discount offered by Prolific
helped to persuade him and his wife that the switch was worth the effort. If
careful and well-informed investors can lose a substantial amount from what
should be such a simple transaction, what hope is there for others?
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XIX
</PAGE>
