<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 91 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (23): Financing a
family idyll - Serious Riches / It's been based on: acumen, luck and joint
decisions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MONEY IS not the only currency,' observes Christopher Lloyd Owen. 'You can
be stinking mega-rich and unhappy.'
Mr Lloyd Owen is certainly not unhappy. Whether he qualifies as 'stinking
mega-rich' is another matter; but life's adventures have left him, at the
age of 38, with a seven-bedroom Jacobean house, tucked between the few hills
surrounding Norwich, and a considerable clutch of investments.
More important, he is happily married to his wife, Antonia, and has two
children - Edward, 10, and Rose, seven. All business decisions are taken
jointly, he says.
Business acumen, coupled, as he freely admits, with luck, built the family's
prosperity. After school at Winchester and university at the Courtauld
Institute in London, where he was taught by Anthony Blunt, he worked as an
art dealer for 10 years, and then built up small businesses, in London and
then in Norfolk.
It is vital to the philosophy guiding Mr Lloyd Owen's personal finances that
he lives his life, and tailors his finances to fit it - never the other way
around.
Business and finance are discussed thoughtfully and incisively, but opinions
on less dry subjects have a habit of bursting up into the conversation.
Topics include his wife, his children, animals, art, particularly bird art,
gardening, and shooting. The family home - crammed with prints, paintings,
and ornaments - bears testament to his earlier career as an art dealer. Six
sofas show that the family has been lucky to receive a number of legacies.
The house - his fourth  - is also the best example of the part luck has
played in the family's good fortune. He has bought all the four houses he
has ever viewed.
All the moves accidentally took advantage of property price moves. The first
two homes were in Wandsworth, before the yuppies moved in. Then the family
went to Battersea, just before gentrification had reached that far. In 1986,
at last able to move back to Norfolk where he had been brought up, he viewed
his present house, fell in love with it, and bought it with cash. Over the
following year, East Anglian property values almost doubled.
He has a Pounds 30,000 mortgage to take advantage of mortgage interest tax
relief, but has otherwise avoided debt to finance property buying.
He scorns speculative property investment, and does not intend to buy a
second house. 'I would have thought for most people their home would be a
sufficient property investment.
His conservative investment philosophy ensures the family's idyllic
lifestyle can continue. Mr Lloyd Owen took out a pension when he was 32,
which is now building 'nicely thank you'. But it was a wrench: 'It's very
hard for anyone to realise they are going to be 65. I forced myself to start
a pension, but every time you pay it out it's dead money.'
He runs the pension fund through his company, for himself, via Standard
Life.
This is the family's only collective investment. Unit trusts he considers
'dull and grey'. 'Imagine you had Pounds 5,000 to invest and you bought
Pounds 5,000 in UK equity units from some manager. How dull] Wouldn't it be
more fun to have Pounds 2,500 in BP and Pounds 2,500 in Marks and Spencer?'
He expands: 'If you have a portfolio of UK equities with a reasonable
spread, you've done exactly what the unit trusts have done. They have only
put several eggs in one basket.
He admits the worth of unit trusts for investing in foreign situations, but
resists moves by brokers in this direction.
'We hold a reasonably balanced British equity portfolio - haven't the
share-owning classes been owning British equities since the coffee-houses
started?
'Someone once told me the stock market is only the upper class betting shop.
At that time I was rather horrified. But there's a grain of truth in it.
'As investors, our balance is almost entirely widows and orphans stocks  -
blue chip companies like ICI, Guinness and Glaxo. We were both brought up
with the old-fashioned ideas that you should never sell capital and neither
a borrower nor a lender be. And we are too busy living life to bother with
short-term gambles and speculations.'
Their portfolio was for many years handled by Grieveson Grant, which joined
Kleinwort Benson at Big Bang. Mr Lloyd Owen then left Kleinworts for Laing &amp;
Cruickshank, and now also uses a broker in Norwich.
His reasons are clear and trenchantly expressed - some London brokers are
over-charging, and the future for small investors lies with regional
stockbrokers: 'I think the London brokers have decided not to give the
client what he wants, because their main fee income comes form corporate
work. The small client is having to pay huge fees for analysts.
'The provincial firm, because they don't employ analysts and don't have to
pay Pounds 120 a square foot, I believe is going to end up as the best
stockbroker. I think they will serve the small investors best.
'We left Kleinwort Benson when their fee became ridiculous. It was going to
be a third of the income from the portfolio, even if they neither bought nor
sold a share.'
He is also 'heavily into Peps'. 'Anyone with a portfolio who doesn't
annually move a small amount into a Pep is a fool.' The brokers are
instructed to boost the Lloyd Owens' Peps to their capacity every year.
The only other big investment goes towards schooling. At present, Edward is
at prep school in Northamptonshire, and Rose is still at a local village
school. Having made the decision to pursue a private education for their
children, the Lloyd Owens put a lump-sum into a school-fees capital scheme.
'We might have been able to do as well elsewhere, but we've also got a life
to lead, and the scheme is going to do it for us. At the beginning of every
term, we will get a handsome cheque. We can't get at the lump sum, but it's
done.'
Prudence over life's most weighty concerns means bland practicality never
stands in the way of a light impulse, as two delicate, and beautiful African
red-eared waxbills in the corner of the Lloyd Owen kitchen could testify. He
saw them while in a pet-shop to buy dog-food, and fell in love with them. He
bought a cage at the same time, and carried them home.
Impulse buying was off the agenda when he was an art dealer. Dealers, unlike
an auctioneers, own their own art.
Dealing is not for the faint-hearted, particularly if, as in Mr Lloyd Owen's
case, you work on your own account. 'The problem is that, to be a London art
dealer, you do not just need weekend money; you need quite major financing
if you want to buy really good pictures, which is why quite a lot of London
art dealers work for a bank.
'It's a very bad investment, art, anyway. You should never buy a picture for
an investment. Only buy a picture if you like it. You should only buy a
picture as an investment if you are a dealer - then you have a chance to
make a profit out of it. Buying any object for an investment is a gamble.
'I stopped because I could no longer afford to buy the pictures I wanted,
because I had just got married. That was in 1978. It was great fun - I was
very much what you might call a dealer's dealer. I owned shares in pictures
and bought from one dealer and sold to another, rather than having private
customers.'
Most dealings on his own account were in English Victorian painters, of whom
Frith, best known for 'Derby Day', was an example.
Mr Lloyd Owen says the experience taught him one thing: 'You have never sold
a painting until you have got the money. There are a lot of companies out
there supplying goods and having their customers going bust on them. It's
given me extraordinary caution about giving credit to people. If you work on
normal profit-margins and you do not get paid for 70 days, I would rather
not have the deal.'
This provides a direct line to the core of his current finances, his two
companies, both of which seem far-removed from the world of high art.
One, Promotion Sourcing Ltd, is owned entirely by the Lloyd Owens. It
supplies companies with promotional gifts, such as golf-balls, diaries or
beer coasters emblazoned with the company logo. 'I went into that in 1983
when I acquired 50 per cent of the equity. In 1985, I bought my co-partner
out of it.'
Then came the chance to buy into Hangar Press, a Norwich litho printer which
now shares a building with Promotion Sourcing. 'That's constituted as a
partnership. They are different organisations because I have a partner in
Hangar Press.
'We are keen on credit control, and we have minimal borrowings. We don't
bleed the business dry. The two companies have a workforce of 11 - and I
have cracking good employees. They are your most important investment, and
your biggest expense. We have great fun at work, and we make money.'
Christopher Lloyd Owen is a 'hands-on' businessman, and regards the
companies as the major financial effort in his family's life: 'They have to
be. And in a way, apart from providing us with an income, they are the only
bit of thinking financially that we do about inheritance. Selling out the
business could be my pension fund. We are conscious of that.
'But if you can have fun on the way ..'
'Imagine you had Pounds 5,000 to invest and you bought Pounds 5,000 in UK
equity units from some manager,' says Christopher Lloyd Owen 'How dull]
Wouldn't it be more fun to have Pounds 2,500 in BP and Pounds 2,500 in Marks
and Spencer?' Even a careful and well informed investor can lose money on
what ought to be a routine operation. Ron Boyce switched his Pounds 2,853
unit trust investment into a Pep, and it cost him Pounds 248
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XVIII Photograph (Omitted). Photograph (Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-2997</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BDZA8AE3FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910426
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 91 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (22): A simple way
into global bonds - Unit Trusts / Recessions are traditionally a good time
to buy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IT HAS become something of an old saw that, for unit trusts, 'past
performance is no guide to future prospects'.
Managers who specialise in international bonds, however, are only too
pleased to tell this to clients, because performance in this sector has
historically been poor, and was particularly bad in 1990. Nevertheless, a
number of management groups, including Mercury, Barings, Newton and
Fidelity, launched new global bond unit trusts earlier this year.
The unit-trust international fixed interest sector dropped by an average of
6.2 per cent during 1990, according to Micropal. The sector has shown an
increase of only 20.2 per cent over the last five years on Micropal's
estimates. Over the last 10 years, it ranks 12th out of 19 sectors.
Bond trusts also consistently under-perform the market as represented by the
JP Morgan Government Bond Index. In the last five years, the index has
returned 24.97 per cent - 4 per cent better than the average bond unit
trust. In the last 12 months, the index has lost only 1.74 per cent,
out-performing by almost 5 per cent unit trusts, which are weighed down by
management fees.
Financial advisers have retained some hostility towards the trusts, because
of the high fees. Alan Torevell, of Torevell Mahon Granville, says that
exchange-rate risks have been understated by managers; while Peter Smith, of
Hill Martin, baulks at the front-end fees - he suggests buying bonds via
European banks.
However, trusts still provide the most practical way for small investors to
tap international bonds. This is because several bonds need to be held in
order to gain a 'spread' of risk, and deals are usually made in massive
amounts - for example, French government bonds normally change hands in
units of FFr10m (around Pounds 1m).
The need to hold currency reserves - made considerably less important by the
UK's full entry into the European Monetary System - in order to hedge
against exchange-rate fluctuations also makes it difficult for a private
investor to get involved.
Bonds are still not good long-term investments, as the BZW gilt-equity study
makes clear - Pounds 100 invested in gilts in 1918 would now be worth Pounds
47.30, while the same amount invested in equities would be priced at Pounds
8,039.20.
But the same survey shows the best annual price increases in UK gilts all
followed the trough of a recession: 1932, when prices rose 35.6 per cent;
1977 (30.6 per cent); and 1982 (36.2 per cent).
Recessions are traditionally good times to buy bonds. Interest rates are now
high, and the best time to buy into the bond market is when rates are about
to fall. When interest rates are high, investors need a high rate of return,
or 'yield', from bonds to tempt them away from other investments. As the
amount paid out each year is fixed, this can only be done by cutting the
price.
When interest rates fall, bond prices rise again. This explains recent
increased interest in UK gilts.
David Rosier, managing director of Mercury Asset Management, put it this
way: 'It was exactly this scenario that we had in 1982. Economic activity
was absolutely flat. The gilt-edged market in 1982 returned 52 per cent,
whereas the All-Share index returned about 30 per cent.'
Nicholas Henderson, head of fixed income at Gartmore, says: 'Where we are
now, with real yields very high, the Anglo-Saxon economies in recession, and
inflation falling, we think it's a very attractive environment for the
global bond investor.' He adds that 1990 was a bad year for bonds, because
the German government issued debt in order to finance reunification, and
raised interest rates. So prices fell.
There are strong arguments for investing in foreign government securities,
and not UK gilts, thanks to the UK's relatively high rate of inflation.
Inflation reduces the 'real yield' received by the investor.
Mr Rosier explains: 'If you look at inflation in this country, it is 9.5 per
cent. The yield on gilts is 10.5 or 11 per cent, so you are getting about 1
per cent real yield.
'French inflation is about 3 per cent, but the yield on French government
bonds is about 9 per cent. We think the opportunities for capital gains are
greater in international bonds, because of the real yields available.'
Paul Sheehan, manager of Newton Investment Management's fund, puts real
yields from French bonds at 9.2 per cent, and from Dutch bonds at 9.3 per
cent. He, like most of the other fund managers, will be concentrating on
European bonds.
He also notes that, since October, bond prices have already risen by 10 per
cent in the US, and by 15 per cent in Japan. European bond prices have yet
to start increasing.
Hambros Bank's model suggests that the optimum time for investing in bonds
may already have passed. This certainly seems to be the case in the
Anglo-Saxon economies, while European markets will not offer such good value
for much longer.
Mr Henderson admits that bonds have never outperformed equities over a
10-year period, and does not see this happening in the future. However, he
does see bonds as an ideal alternative to cash over a medium-term
perspective of two or three years, when equities may still be in poor
health.
Over this time-scale, global bonds trusts could provide one of the few
routes to a substantial gain, along with a welcome degree of security.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XVII Graph (Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-2998</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BDZA8AE2FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910426
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 91 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (21): A simple but
impertinent way into blue-chips with the Woolwich - Unit Trusts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WOOLWICH Building Society attempted in January to simplify the world of unit
trusts with the launch of its Stockmarket fund.
Investors are able to buy and sell units at their local building society
branches, with the help of a plastic card, which can also be used to get an
update on the value of their holdings. Contract notes are being issued, but
no unit certificates.
There is only one fund on offer, which will invest largely in UK blue chips
and will be managed by Mercury Asset Management. There is a minimum
investment of Pounds 500, or monthly savings of Pounds 25. In addition, a
special account has been established, where only the interest is invested in
the fund.
So far, over Pounds 10m has been raised and the Woolwich says it is 'on
target' for 50,000 account holders in the first year. The majority of
accounts opened have been personal equity plans, and there is a a high
proportion of regular savings plans.
However, after all the effort that was involved in establishing the fund, it
was a pity that the Woolwich did not eliminate one obvious drawback. Savers
in the Woolwich Prime Gold account, the main savings account, might imagine
that they can simply transfer a monthly payment from their savings into the
new fund.
But that is not possible. They can transfer money from their bank account,
or they can invest a lump sum. Alternatively, they could open a Woolwich
current account, transfer the money from the savings account to the current
account, and then transfer again into the stock market fund.
This last solution, however, means that savers have to fill in a
current-account application form, which means answering a vast number of
impertinent questions about their salaries and past employers. To endure so
much questioning for the privilege of giving the Woolwich money seems well
beyond the call of duty.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
