<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 91 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (19): Absorbing and
confusing - Mergers and buy-outs play havoc with portfolios / Equities,
French Market Profile
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FRENCH FUND managers and individual shareholders have watched helplessly
over the last year, as the list of stocks in their portfolios has changed
and dwindled without any intervention on their part.
A wave of mergers and buy-outs has eliminated from the French stock-exchange
list a growing number of companies ' often already controlled, clearly or in
practice, by a larger group, but nevertheless in many cases interesting
components for a fund manager's portfolio.
Under France's merger process, one company can be absorbed into another
following a vote at a shareholders' meeting. Minority shareholders who might
want to hold on to their shares have no choice.
This process has in recent months seen the absorption of Dumez, the
construction company, into Lyonnaise des Eaux, the water group; or Facom, a
maker of hand-tools, into Strafor, the office furniture group; of Compagnie
Francaise de l'Afrique Occidentale (CFAO), the distribution and African
trading company, into Pinault, the timber group.
More recently, Alcatel Alsthom, the electrical engineering and
telecommunications group, has announced plans to absorb three of its listed
subsidiaries, including Generale Occidentale, formerly the holding company
of Sir James Goldsmith. Total, the oil major, plans to do the same with its
portfolio holding company Omnium Financier de Paris.
Paribas, the investment banking group, adopted a different procedure. Rather
than merging, it chose to offer its own shares in exchange for those of
Poliet and Ciments Francais, two building material companies which it
already controlled.
Although this technique leaves minority shareholders with the option of
hanging on to their shares, this particular deal caused even greater
annoyance, especially among foreign fund managers. After selecting a cement
or construction investment for their portfolio, most were furious at being
offered an exit into a banking stock.
Although this wave of mergers and buy-outs has provoked laments in the
French financial press about the dwindling choice offered to investors on
the Paris stock exchange, however, some investors have viewed it as a
healthy reorganisation of the stock-exchange list. One of the problems with
the Paris market, these commentators remark, is that so many of the
companies listed on the exchange are controlled by other companies.
French investors seem not to worry too much about their lack of voting power
in a wholly-controlled company ' wrongly, perhaps, in the light of the
numerous occasions in recent years, when minority shareholders have been
royally fleeced by the dominant shareholder ' but at the very least, this
state of affairs reduces the liquidity of the stock.
Often, particularly on the second market, the free float of shares is less
than 15 per cent, making it impossible for major investors to deal in any
significant size.
Even among the bigger companies which are not wholly controlled, a formal or
informal pact among the 'hard core' friendly shareholders often reduces the
real free float to 50 per cent or less. Bank of France statistics suggest
that 35 per cent of listed shares in 1989 were owned by individuals, 20 per
cent by institutional investors, 21 per cent by industrial and commercial
companies and 23 per cent by foreigners. But stockbrokers DLP James Capel
estimate that 50 per cent of the real float of the shares making up the
CAC-40 index are held by foreigners.
Among French investors, the statistics are open to some interpretation. The
latest figures for the number of individual shareowners stand at around 6m,
but these date back to 1988, just after the series of privatisations which
brought a wave of new investors into the equity market for the first time '
Paribas alone attracted 3.8m small shareholders on its privatisation in
1987.
Many of these neophyte shareholders have since sold out, or transferred
their holdings into mutual funds, which account for around 8 per cent of
equity investment.
France's mutual fund industry as a whole is larger than the rest of Europe's
put together, with over FFr1,444bn (Pounds 142.80bn) under management at the
end of January in Sicavs, or Societes d'Investissement a Capitaux Variables
(the main form of mutual fund), according to Europerformance, the specialist
organisation which monitors the sector.
However, the bulk of this money ' FFr1,052bn ' is invested in money-market
or bond funds. French equity funds are much weaker, and several French banks
have gone to the UK to look for additional equity fund-management expertise:
Societe Generale, the big high-street bank, acquired Touche Remnant, Banque
Indosuez, the investment banking arm of the Suez group, bought Gartmore, and
Credit Commercial de France, the medium-sized commercial bank, took over
Framlington.
The Commission des Operations de Bourse (COB) says the amount of money
invested through Sicavs in French shares plunged in the first nine months of
last year by FFr40bn, to finish up at only FFr102bn at the end of September.
One of the problems is that the government's latest tax-sheltered savings
plan, the highly successful Plan d'Epargne Populaire, or Pep, is designed
more to help fixed-interest investment ' unlike its predecessors, the Monory
plan or the Delors Compte d'Epargne en Actions, which explicitly set out to
boost equity investment. Savers are putting their money either in the Pep,
which attracted FFr105bn last year, or in short-term money-market Sicavs.
This has not stopped the CAC-40 index from climbing back to a band around
1850, but as companies start to call for cash ' such as Beghin-Say with a
FFr3bn combined rights and convertible bond issue ' it puts a crimp in the
flow of funds into the equity market. If the Paris index is to reach again
the peak of 2141 it achieved a year ago, it will depend heavily on new
investment from foreign institutions to fill this gap.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
