<PROFILE>_AN-BDZA8AEYFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910426
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 91 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (17): Sweden and
Spain record the biggest gains in a mixed Europe / Equities
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM COCHRANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EUROPE excluding the UK, as measured by the FT-Actuaries World Indices,
showed a total return of 13.8 per cent in sterling terms in the first
quarter. Measured in local currency, January was just 1 per cen higher;
February saw a rise of 11.9 per cent; but the climb slowed to 2.4 per cent
in March.
The quarter began with the same caution that had followed the slide in
equities which began in August and the Iraqi invasion of Kuwait. The
European market also shivered on January 11, as Soviet troops moved on key
installations in Lithunia; and it took its time about reacting to open
warfare in the Gulf, which began less than a week later.
Optimism about an early end to the war brought the gains in February, which
were consolidated and improved on in March. However, the FT-SE Eurotrack 100
index was actually a little lower at the end of March than it had been
nearly three weeks earlier.
The quarter saw wide variations between countries, with Sweden and Spain (up
28.5 and 26.5 per cent respectively) at the top of the list, and Norway and
Germany (up 8.3 and 7.7 per cent) at the bottom.
Sweden's economy, by the second half of last year, had been heading into
recession, with foreign investors withdrawing from its former high-flyers,
international blue chips such as the telecommunications group Ericsson. This
year, however, domestic financial institutions, flush with cash, have
returned to the home equity market. The economic and fiscal position has
improved, and there has been a spate of corporate activity to excite equity
investors.
In Spain, the economic squeeze imposed on consumers as long ago as 1988 has
borne fruit. Early in March, the strength of the peseta, the prospect of an
interest-rate cut and an improvement in the inflation figures took the
market up by some 8 per cent over eight days.
Brokers Barclays de Zoete Wedd said this month, in its continental European
strategy monthly, that for those with an upbeat view on the dollar, Norway's
shipping, oils and metals (where profits and asset values are dollar
sensitive) provide significant gearing to dollar strength. 'Our view,' they
said, 'is that this is more a story for 1992.'
Germany has moved from euphoria to gloom. Between the peak of Ostphantasie,
in March 1990, and the end of the year, its DAX blue-chip index dropped by
29 per cent, as hopes for the domestic market were replaced by anxiety about
international recession and its effect on big overseas producers such as the
chemicals company BASF or exporters such as Volkswagen.
This year, the market has laboured under the burden of reunification costs.
There have been estimates that the growth rate in Germany's GNP could fall
by between 0.5 and 1 percentage point. Tax increases that will pay for
restoring the former east Germany to health are expected to complicate a
wage negotiation round, which is already potentially acrimonious. And the
weakness of the Deutsche Mark shows how uncertain the economy has become.
For the rest, there are a range of opinions. BZW expects Europe to hold up
against the world index after what it sees as 12 months of underperformance.
Kleinwort Benson is 'generally bearish' but adding: 'The markets are set for
a period of consolidation after their recent strong run, but we do not
look for a significant setback in view of continuing high levels of
liquidity.'
Mr David Roche, of Morgan Stanley, has advised his clients to go underweight
in equities and raise cash, or to lock in profits using derivatives. 'In the
past 10 years,' he said in a mid-March EuroLetter, 'dividends have grown
faster than profits, which grew faster than national income. In the next
five years this order will be reversed.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XIV Photograph (Omitted). Graph (Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
