<DOCNO>FT911-3003</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BDZA8AEXFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910426
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 91 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (16): Liquidity
pours in as US investors believe the worst is over / Equities
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HAVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
'WOW, WHAT a Quarter]' screamed the headline on Barron's, the US business
weekly. It summed up Wall Street's reaction to the performance of US stocks
in the first three months of 1991.
Between New Year and the end of March, the Dow Jones Industrial Average rose
10.6 per cent, the Standard &amp; Poor's 500 13.6 per cent, and the Nasdaq
composite of over-the-counter stocks a record 29 per cent.
The main driving-force behind soaring stock values was an injection of
liquidity into the market at the start of the year. In the face of recession
at home, imminent war in the Gulf, declining corporate profitability and a
banking crisis, institutional and individual investors decided that the time
was right to put their money back into equities.
The reason: they felt things couldn't get any worse, that the bottom of the
recession was near, and that interest rates - already on their way down -
would continue to fall.
Money poured into the market from institutions, but especially from the big
investment funds, which benefited from an inflow of Dollars 3.1bn of private
investors' money during February alone.
The biggest winners were secondary stocks, perceived by investors to be
undervalued and offering the best earnings potential, and the Nasdaq market,
which saw average daily volume jump to a record 161m. Medical and
bio-technology stocks led the way, while on the Big Board financial stocks
shone.
Yet the market's ride has not been uniformly smooth. The year opened badly
as worries about the approaching quarterly corporate reporting season and
the effect of war on the economy sparked a 130-point decline in the first
two weeks. The onset of hostilities in the Middle East changed everything.
The Dow rose nearly 400 points on a wave of patriotic buying. The war and
recession were seen to have been discounted by the market, which was looking
forward six months to a period of peace and economic growth.
At the beginning of March, prices retreated on inflation worries,
profit-taking and some disturbing employment figures. The bulls returned,
however, after the Federal Reserve cut interest rates to stimulate economic
activity.
Yet the quarter had one nasty shock left up its sleeve: an unexpected
profits warning from IBM in late March, which sent the Dow spinning 60
points lower. However, the market's resilience since then, spurred by the
first signs of a recovery in consumer confidence, has persuaded Wall Street
that the rise in stocks since January has not been a bear market rally, but
the beginning of a fully-fledged bull market.
As for the second quarter, the opening days of April could give us a clue as
to what to expect. The Dow jumped 63 points one day, and dropped 18 points
the next. As the economy slowly chugs into life, analysts expect shares to
keep going up, but not in a straight line.
In Canada, the picture was similar to that seen in the US; the Toronto Stock
Exchange 300 index rose 7.3 per cent during the quarter, with smaller
capitalised stocks making up good ground.
In Mexico, the strong market showing at the end of last year was maintained
during the first quarter of 1991. The Bolsa Index rose 35 per cent between
January and March. According to DA Campbell, the US broking house which
specialises in the Mexican mar ket, the gains have been fuelled by strong
new demand from overseas investors, an economy growing at a rate of 5 per
cent a year, a series of imminent privatisations, and anticipation of a more
liberal regulatory climate.
Much of the renewed interest in Mexico has been stimulated by the
approaching flotation of the remaining shares of Telefonos de Mexico, which
makes up 18 per cent of the Bolsa index. The government is planning a global
offering of 25-30 per cent of the company, and demand for the stock in the
first quarter boosted Telmex's share price by over 50 per cent.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XIV Graph (Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-3004</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BDZA8AEWFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910426
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 91 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (15): London's
advance is part of a global re-rating of markets - Equities
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY BYLAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FOR THOSE investors who got it right, the first quarter of 1991 has joined
the London stock market's roll of honour.
Total returns on equities for the three months have been bettered on only
four occasions in the past decade, according to Barclays de Zoete Wedd. A
combination of lower UK interest rates, reduced pessimism over recessionary
pressures and the swift ending of the Gulf war proved very favourable for
investors.
The FT Actuaries All-Share Index returned 16.9 per cent for the quarter, the
FT-SE 100 Index 16 per cent. As the period drew to its close, the Footsie
was reaching forward daily to new all-time peaks, and retail investment
interest in UK equities was maintaining the welcome return to levels
regarded as viable, if not necessarily hugely profitable, for the London
securities industry.
However, as the quarter ended, the FT-A All-Share index was still about two
points below its peak and, in sterling terms, the UK underperformed the rest
of the world by about 4.5 per cent.
This focus on the broader-based market index, and on sterling values, has
much to say about the performance of UK equities. The advance in London was
part of a global re-rating of equity markets, reflecting a number of
factors, including the speedy end to the fighting in the Gulf and the
powerful rise in the dollar towards the end of the quarter.
The shift in currency values was a double-handed boon to the UK stock
market. The strength of the US currency boosted prospects for the big
dollar-earners which provide about a quarter of the aggregate earnings of
the Footsie list. At the same time, sterling's improvement within the ERM
currency table enhanced the opportunities for cutting UK base rates.
Base rates were cut three times during the quarter, to bring UK rates down
to 12.5 per cent by the end of March, with the equity market clamouring for
further cuts. The half-point cut in base rates just after Budget day
overshadowed the Budget itself, which was seen as neutral for the stock
market.
All equity sectors achieved positive returns over the period. But lower base
rates failed to inspire property shares, which underperformed the All-Share
by 9.9 per cent. Weakest of all were oil shares, which underperformed the
All-Share by 10.4 per cent - not, strangely, because of the Gulf conflict,
but rather because of negative views on crude-oil prices.
The successes ranged across the dollar-earning stocks, with Glaxo, Hanson,
BAT Industries, RTZ and Reuters Holdings prominent, to sectors recovering
from previous misfortune, such as engineering, textile and even contracting
and construction stocks.
As the market moved into the second quarter of 1991, some murmurs of
uncertainty could be heard in the City of London. The outlook for the US
dollar was less clear, and the Gulf war was now history. On the home front,
another half-point cut in UK base rates was expected, but 'the next move
down may be several months in coming,' commented the strategy team at BZW.
And there was a question-mark over German interest rates.
Institutions successful in equities in the first quarter may find other
opportunities ahead. More rights issues are likely to follow the Pounds 2bn
of the first three months, and the estimated Pounds 8bn public sector
borrowing requirement implies significant gilt-edged funding. Mr Ian
Harnett, at Societe Generale Strauss Turnbull, notes that if institutions
now switch into cash, they will effectively secure the return on a FT-SE
level of 2,650 for the year-end without needing to risk further investment
in equities.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XIII Graph (Omitted). Graph (Omitted). Illustration (Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-3005</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BDZA8AEVFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910426
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 91 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (14): Now it's time
to stop and think - The ascent has been dramatic and the analysts are
bullish, but . . . / Equities
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DOMINICK COYLE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CHART says it all. From Mexico to Germany, not a negative mark in sight
in terms of total sterling return for the first quarter of the year.
Equities have been humming right across the world, with some quite
exceptional performances in many markets, not least Hong Kong, Singapore and
Sweden, each showing a return of more than 30 per cent.
The world investment market, excluding the United Kingdom, as measured by
the FT-Actuaries World Index, showed a January-March sterling return of more
than 22 per cent. The UK itself produced a 17 per cent return.
Suddenly, it seems, spring has come to the investment air. The suggestion in
this space in the last Review, that good bargains were to be had in many
markets, but notably in the UK, Spain, France, Germany and Japan, has been
proved right, with gains ranging from a relatively modest (given the cost
and problems of creating a single country) 5 per cent for Germany to almost
28 per cent in Spain.
The advance continued into the first trading days of the present quarter.
London, as measured by the Footsie index, had new highs on three successive
days earlier this month. A number of major markets hit a 1991 high in the
first week of April, including France, the Netherlands, Switzerland, Belgium
and Austria.
The global stock-market advance took many fund managers and individual
investors by surprise, and was certainly more rapid than expected. Markets
continued to show their preference for declining inflation, and may even
continue to rise in the face of somewhat disappointing corporate-earnings
prospects.
Caution says that the sharp rise in the 1991 first quarter must lead to a
pause, and a number of uncertainties do remain - not least the political
situation in the Soviet Union, which is seen as having a particular
influence on the German market.
Yet Goldman Sachs is almost lyrical in its World Investment Strategy
Highlights for April. 'We remain of the view that global equity markets are
at the 'beginning of the matter'. The 20 per cent advance from their lows
marks what we believe to be the beginning of a global equity bull market.
The move, coming as it does at a time of historically low and declining
inflation and interest rates, is wholly consistent with prior bull-market
advances.'
The herd instinct is in full bull-run, and this is always a time for some
hesitation. Most analysts are suddenly pointing towards an investment
nirvana - so it may be the moment to check that the lifeboats are available
if needed, or at least to test the waters selectively. To expect the first
quarter's global gains of more than 20 per cent to continue throughout the
year seems a risky forecast.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
