<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 91 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (12): Make the most
of high interest - Tessas / A few fixed-rate deals are still available
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SARA WEBB
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GIVEN THAT base rates are coming down, many savers are no doubt wishing they
had locked into fixed-rate savings at the start of the year.
Three separate base-rate cuts in February and March - adding up to a 1.5
percentage points and taking the base rate down to 12.5 per cent - have
naturally taken their toll on savings rates.
Many of the tax-exempt special savings accounts (Tessas) either lowered
their rates or stayed put. Competition between banks and building societies
in the Tessa market is particularly keen, and they are reluctant to risk
losing customers by lowering the interest rate.
For savers who want to lock into a high interest rate, there are a few banks
offering fixed-rate Tessas.
Confederation Bank (tel 0438 744-238) has a five-year fixed-rate Tessa with
a gross compound annual rate (CAR) of 11.25 per cent. You have to invest a
lump sum of Pounds 8,040 and, each year, the appropriate sum is switched
into the Tessa from a feeder account. The rate on the feeder account is also
fixed at 11.25 per cent, but remember that interest on feeder accounts is
liable to income tax if you are a taxpayer. The penalty for transfer or
closure is 180 days' interest.
National Mortgage Bank (tel 021 712-2800) recently launched a five-year
fixed-rate Tessa, which pays 11 per cent gross CAR. Again, you make your
deposit into a fixed-rate feeder account, but in this case, the minimum
investment is Pounds 5,000. There is a penalty of 180 days' interest for
transfer or early closure.
If you are worried about locking into a fixed rate for five years, Save &amp;
Prosper/Robert Fleming (tel 0800 282-101) have a one-year fixed-rate Tessa.
The rate is fixed at 10.25 per cent gross CAR, and after one year you can
choose to switch your money into S &amp; P's variable-rate Tessa or you can opt
for another year at the fixed rate - though bear in mind that the new fixed
rate could be much lower if the base rate has been cut substantially. The
minimum investment is Pounds 500, and the maximum is Pounds 3,000 in the
first year. Interest is credited monthly, and you can withdraw net interest
quarterly if you want. There is a discretionary Pounds 50 penalty for
transfer or closure.
Bear in mind, too, that S &amp; P's fixed rate of 10.25 per cent is well below
the 12.18 per cent gross CAR being offered on its variable rate Tessa, and
that many variable-rate Tessas on the market are offering 15 per cent or
more. No one is giving any clues as to whether they will be lowering their
rates in the near future, so it is rather a gamble. However, if you do
decide to plump for a variable-rate Tessa, you would be wise to choose one
with no transfer penalties, as this will allow you to move your money into
the most competitive Tessa at short notice.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page X
</PAGE>
