<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 91 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (11): A debt may
well be good for us - Paying off the mortgage / Basic-rate taxpayers should
look before they leap
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
OUR PARENTS probably told us to stay out of debt if we possibly could. Good
advice, in the main. However, one kind of debt may be worth clinging to -
the mortgage.
Many people realise this, as is shown by a survey conducted by Mori for
Scottish Amicable, the life insurance group. Asked how they would use a
Pounds 30,000 windfall, 42 per cent of respondents said none of it would go
towards repaying their mortgage. Only 13 per cent said all of it would.
The proportion who would repay rose with the size of the mortgage. Only 31
per cent of those with a Pounds 40,000 mortgage said they would not break
into their windfall to repay any of the loan, while 28 per cent said it
would all be used to reduce the debt. This suggests that people are well
informed about mortgages. On loans up to Pounds 30,000, tax relief on the
interest makes them very cheap debts - despite the Budget - but the net
interest rates paid on larger loans are worth avoiding. This is shown by
comparing the real rate of interest paid on a home loan, after mortgage
interest tax relief, with the rates of interest available elsewhere.
On the first Pounds 30,000 of a mortgage, the net interest rate after
mortgage-interest tax relief, is currently 10.31 per cent, according to the
Building Societies Association. This will become better value if interest
rates continue to fall.
If any kind of debt makes you lie awake at night, then it is probably best
to pay off the mortgage as soon as you have the cash to do so. However, some
people, including mortgage-lenders themselves, argue that this approach is
unnecessarily prudent, because you should be able to find a safe alternative
investment that offers a higher rate of interest than you pay on your
mortgage - for example, tax-exempt special saver accounts (Tessas),
index-linked gilts or national saving certificates.
Steven Berry, of Hill Martin, points out that the new regime of independent
taxation and the abolition of composite rate tax on building-society
accounts for non-taxpayers, have made this easier - a non-tax-paying spouse
can receive some interest gross, while paying off debt net of tax.
By investing in this way a sum that might otherwise be used to reduce a
mortgage, you still have the cash in hand. For as long as you have a
mortgage, your building society is available to help with loans for
home-improvements or repairs.
John Bridel, adviser with Towry Law, adds: 'Very often one should keep the
funding vehicle going, anyway.' He points out that you should not
necessarily repay endowment-linked mortgages in full, as you will lose the
terminal bonus of the life insurance policy linked to the mortgage.
The money put towards the life policy makes up a relatively small percentage
of the total monthly payments, points out Mr Bridel; but the balance of the
final maturity value, after you have paid off the loan, could be very useful
 -for instance, to invest for retirement income. The terminal bonus, which
could be lost, makes up much of the return from with-profits policies.
Sometimes, too, one is required to pay an exit-fee when clearing a mortgage.
If you decide to pay off without notice, some lenders may charge a maximum
of an extra three months' interest on redemption. The Building Societies
Association says this would almost certainly be waived in most cases, and
the big societies do not make the charge, but it is as well to check the
small print in your contract. Check, too, on fixed-interest mortgages. The
special arrangements that the lender has made in order to offer a fixed rate
will be thrown awry by early repayment; and a justifiable fee of around
Pounds 100 will normally be payable.
You pay the full gross rate on all of the mortgage that is outstanding above
the Pounds 30,000 limit for mortgage tax relief. Last year, gross mortgage
rates managed to exceed 15 per cent. You are unlikely to find another
investment that can guarantee to match this return - though Tessa rates
appear to be remainining high while mortgage rates come down - so the best
bet is to use any lump sum to pay off any of your mortgage in excess of
Pounds 30,000.
The abolition of top-rate mortgage tax relief has made mortgages
significantly less good value for the very well off, and tax relief must be
subject to continued political risk. Successive governments have allowed the
threshold of Pounds 30,000 to be eaten away by inflation - if it had been
indexed from its rate in 1974, the threshold would now be almost Pounds
120,000, according to Hill Martin - and it might be cut completely by a
Labour government. The Conservatives intend to cut basic-tax rates, which
would reduce the amount of relief.
All such changes shift the logic in favour of repaying more of the mortgage.
But it is worth timing the move carefully if you have a building-society
repayment mortgage, because the societies charge interest on the capital
outstanding at the beginning of their year, and then collect it over the 12
months. On this basis, you should make your repayment towards the end of the
building society year - most societies have a December 31 year-end.
If you are repaying a part of the loan on which you are receiving tax
relief, you should let your tax inspector know as soon as possible, says Mr
Bridel. Otherwise you could find yourself with a big tax bill at the end of
the year.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page X
</PAGE>
