<DOCNO>FT911-3010</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BDZA8AEQFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910426
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 91 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (9): Helping the
homeless - What's New? / . . . with a possible 40% return
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ASSURED-tenancy Business Expansion Scheme survived the Budget without a
scratch. Most advisers had expected these relatively low-risk BES
investments to come under the hammer.
So all the better for House the Homeless of London II, which has launched
its second assured-tenancy scheme. It has two aims: one, to ameliorate the
plight of homeless in the capital and; two, to guarantee a 40 per cent
return on investments.
The scheme is run in conjunction with the Peabody Trust, a registered
charity, founded in 1862. House the Homeless will buy vacant properties on a
leasehold basis, letting them to the homeless. At the end of five years, the
Peabody Trust guarantees to buy the properties at 140 per cent of the asking
price. The risks? As with most assured tenancies, everything hinges on the
viability of the prospective purchaser.
'Peabody Trust has a property portfolio of just under Pounds 1bn and gets
grant of millions of pounds from the government every year,' says Keith
Turpin, of Touche Ross, financial advisers to House the Homeless of London.
But no matter how profitable the company, there is no guarantee that a
change of government will not see off assured tenancy schemes. A sobering
thought, with a general election due next year, if not this.
The biggest Budget boost for the savings industry was aimed at friendly
societies - and children, says Mark Rittner, of financial advisers Rathbone
Brothers. In other investments, 'if a parent makes a gift to a child, the
income on that gift is attributed to the parent and taxable. In friendly
societies, however, the income is solely attributed to the child and
tax-free,' says Mr Rittner.
This year, the chancellor raised the annual tax-free investment level in
friendly societies from Pounds 150 to Pounds 200, and revived the right to
issue children's life policies on a tax-exempt basis. The government imposed
a quota restriction on life policies for children in 1985, the effect of
which was to stop many friendly societies from issuing them.
'We are particularly thrilled,' said Peter Gray, general manager of
Tunbridge Wells Equitable Friendly Society. 'And we are definitely bringing
back a Baby Bond (a bond written on the life of the child, which can be
redeemed at a certain age or continued indefinitely).' Tunbridge Wells
Equitable offers two types of baby bond - a traditional with-profits policy,
and a unit-linked one based almost exclusively in equities.
Clive Scott-Hopkins, of independent advisers Towry Law, recommends Tunbridge
Wells's with profits contract: 'It's very competitive and has been one of
the top 10 performers for years.'
While providing a nest-egg for children is a good idea, and the
friendly-society route a relatively affordable one, parents would do well
also to plan for education. The average annual fees for independent boarding
schools in 1990 was Pounds 6,000, according to statistics from the
Independent Schools Information Service. For independent day schools, the
figure stood at Pounds 3,300.
Educational trusts are a route to be recommended only if you are sure the
money will be used for school fees, and as long as they retain their
charitable status. These conditions met, then Save and Prosper and the
School Fees Insurance Agency have unusual features in their schemes. A
lump-sum buys an annuity to provide termly payments. Although the yields on
this investment are relatively low, income tax, which is usually deducted
from the taxable element of the annuity payments, can be reclaimed.
Parents wishing to provide for their children's future would also be well
advised to examine ways of minimising inheritance tax. M &amp; G's Estate
Protection Plan - a life policy written under trust  - was named the winner
of the Financial Adviser's product of the year award for its user-friendly
and flexible approach. (Financial Adviser is a weekly newspaper for
financial intermediaries, published by the FT).
At its simplest, the plan sets up a trust outside the client's estate,
designed to pay the inheritance tax when it falls due, says David Druce,
life product development manager of M&amp;G. The premiums on the life policy can
be paid in either monthly or annual instalments - or, unusually, in a lump
sum. M &amp; G also produces an easy-to-understand inheritance tax guide, which
was part of the package commended by Financial Adviser judges.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page VIII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-3011</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BDZA8AEPFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910426
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 91 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (8): Beware of the
overdraft trap
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INTEREST RATES are coming down, but in many cases overdraft interest charges
have actually gone up in the last six to nine months. So now may be the time
to look more critically at interest-bearing current accounts.
Interest paid on balances in credit has fallen in quite a striking fashion.
In July last year, Abbey National paid 6.25 per cent gross on all balances
in credit. Today the figure is 4.5 per cent. Girobank paid a net 9 per cent
in July; today it pays 6 per cent.
As amounts to be earned from interest-bearing current accounts on balances
shrink, it is surprising to see that quite a lot of large banks and building
societies have actually raised their overdraft interest rates since last
summer.
This seems hard to justify, and holders of interest-bearing current accounts
seem likely to be especially hard hit: the downside of these accounts is
that overdraft charges, especially for unauthorised overdrafts, are
generally higher than on the old non-interest bearing variety.
The Woolwich Building Society, which has trimmed its overdraft rates, is a
shining exception. Some of the large clearers do fairly well, too: Barclays
and NatWest have held their authorised rates unchanged. Lloyds is planning
to reduce its rates on Monday April 29.
Most other large players in the market have increased their interest-rate
charges since last summer, even though base rates have fallen. A more
glaring injustice is hard to imagine. An unauthorised overdraft on Midland
Orchard or First Direct will now cost you 38.1 per cent (up from 37.6 per
cent last summer). Nationwide Anglia Building Society, with a charge of 39.2
per cent (36.8 per cent last summer) wins by a short head.
Meanwhile, earnings from the accounts are likely to fall. 'All our
interest-bearing accounts have been affected by the base rate moving down
and the abolition of composite rate tax,' says a Lloyds Bank spokesman.
Further falls in base rates will probably mean the attractions of
interest-bearing accounts will be progressively reduced.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
