<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 91 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (4): Three treats
for children
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CHILDREN'S SAVINGS were boosted by three measures in the Budget.
Friendly Societies - offering tax-exempt funds which pay out a tax-free lump
sum after 10 years - will now be allowed to take business from people under
the age of 18. As the Budget also raised the total amount any individual can
put into a society each year to Pounds 200 (this time last year it was
Pounds 100), this branch of the investment industry has been given a
significant shot in the arm.
Experts expect a surge of baby bonds,allowing parents and grandparents to
putmoney into a child's account, to hit the market once the Finance Bill has
received royal assent, which should happen towards the end of July.
Meanwhile, National Savings will launch a new product aimed at youngsters -
a tax-free children's bonus bond. Maximum investment will be Pounds 1,000
per child, in units of Pounds 25 each, and there will be a substantial bonus
paid after five years.
A final measure to benefit all families with children, irrespective of their
income, was the rise in child benefit. From October, families will receive
an extra Pounds 1 for their first child, and an extra 25p for each
subsequent one. Mr Lamont promised that in future the benefit would be
indexed.
</TEXT>
