<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 91 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (2): Fiscal
neutrality rules - The Budget / The aim is to tax employees equally
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BUDGET headlines were stolen by the chancellor's switch of the tax
burden from the community charge to VAT.
But budgets also offer the Treasury and the Inland Revenue the chance to
close old tax loopholes, and to offer new tax incentives. There was no new
product to rival last year's Tessa, but there was plenty to keep the
financial adviser busy.
One prominent area was the continuing crackdown on employee perks. The tax
advantages offered by company cars have been steadily under assault during
the 1980s, and there was a further attack, including the imposition of
employers' national insurance charges, this time. Mobile phones, if
available for personal use, also became a taxable benefit.
The idea is that employees should, in the long run, be taxed equally,
whether they are paid in kind or in cash. This principle of fiscal
neutrality also showed itself when the chancellor abolished higher-rate tax
relief on mortgage interest payments.
That change had been expected for some time, and was softened by the
simultaneous increase in the higher-rate tax threshold. Another area where
action had been widely anticipated was offshore trusts.
By rolling up their investments offshore in a trust, some well-off
individuals had been able to postpone, in some cases virtually indefinitely,
the payment of capital gains tax.
Although it will still be possible to delay tax on an offshore trust's gains
until a capital payment is made to a UK resident beneficiary, a supplemental
charge will be added. This will be, in effect, a charge on the deferred tax
which 'should' previously have been paid on the gains rolling up in the
trust. The charge will be levied at 10 per cent of the deferred tax for
every year, up to a maximum of six, that the gain is held in the trust
before being paid out.
The change will remove many of the apparent advantages of having an offshore
trust; but Caroline Garnham, tax partner with solicitors Taylor Joynson
Garrett, feels that the supplemental charge may be so complicated to
administer that it will be abolished before it reaches the statute book.
The Revenue also produced a consultative document about onshore trusts,
which represented an attempt to simplify the rules on trust taxation. The
general intention is to bring the taxation of trusts in line with that of
individuals.
On this page, we highlight some of the other changes in the Budget. And
articles throughout the Review also include details of Budget announcements,
where relevant.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IV Illustration (Omitted).
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT911-3017</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-BDZA8AEJFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>910426
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 91 / FT Quarterly Review of Personal Finance (5): The changes at
a glance
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Value Added Tax
Payable on most goods, rose by 2.5 points to 17.5 per cent - the first rise
since Sir Geoffrey Howe nearly doubled VAT in 1979.
Poll Tax
Pounds 140 cut from the level previously announced for 1991-92 for every
local authority in Britain; though some did not experience the full benefit,
because they would otherwise have received a rebate. No poll tax is payable
until the new bills have been sent out.
Mortgage-interest tax relief
Abolished at the top rate of 40 per cent. Top-rate taxpayers still receive
basic-rate relief of 25 per cent on the first Pounds 30,000 of a loan - a
threshold unaltered since 1983.
Income Tax
Basic rate (25 per cent) and the top rate at (40 per cent) unchanged.
Personal allowances increased 9.8 per cent, in line with inflation.
The only real change was to the threshold before the top rate tax is
payable: it rose by 14.5 per cent, from Pounds 20,700 to Pounds 23,700,to
soothe those who lost on the reduction in mortgage relief.
Personal equity plans
From January, investors will be able to take out a Pep of up to Pounds 3,000
in a single company, in addition to the Pounds 6,000 plan already allowed.
The restriction that at least half of all Pep investments must be in UK
equities will change some time later in the year. Thereafter, half of your
investment must be in the EC. A Pep can now hold Pounds 9,000 of shares in
non-UK companies.
Share-ownership schemes
discount on executive share-ownership schemes, if they introduce a
share-ownership scheme for their employees. The scope for profit-sharing
schemes and profit-related pay will also increase.
Offshore trusts
to clamp down on these tax shelters. Assets from existing onshore trusts are
now liable to a tax charge when transferred offshore, and the settlor to a
trust is liable to capital gains tax if he, or any of his family or his
companies, is a beneficiary.
Capital Gains Tax
The threshold before tax is payable on gains increased 10 per cent to Pounds
5,500 for individuals. Trustees are immune from tax on their first Pounds
2,750 in gains (another 10 per cent increase). Allowable gains from letting
rooms were doubled to Pounds 40,000. Retirement relief (when an individual
surrenders an interest in a business following retirement) was increased
from Pounds 125,000 to Pounds 150,000,and is now claimable at the age of 55,
not 60.
Inheritance Tax
An indexed increase in the threshold before IHT is payable,from Pounds
128,000 to Pounds 140,000, was made.
High-street shares
Submissions have been invited for a plan to sell shares from high-street
retail outlets. If a good offer is forthcoming,the sell-off of the
government's remaining holding in British Telecom may be handled this way.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IV
</PAGE>
