<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 91 / Commodities and Agriculture: Smelters work close to capacity
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KENNETH GOODING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WESTERN EUROPE'S primary aluminium smelters continued to work close to the
limits of their capacity last year, according to the European Aluminium
Association.
Output slipped by only 0.5 per cent from the 1989 level, from 3.58m tonnes
to 3.56m, it reports.
The Dusseldorf-based association monitors the aluminium industries in
Austria, France, Germany, Greece, Iceland, Italy, the Netherlands, Norway,
Spain, Sweden, Switzerland, the UK and Yugoslavia.
This year low aluminium prices are putting considerable pressure on the
European industry, which is estimated to have the world's highest-cost
smelters.
In its latest Aluminium Annual Review, the Anthony Bird consultancy group
suggested that Italy has the highest-cost smelters with costs of 78 cents a
lb, followed by Spain and Germany at 76 cents, and France at 70 cents. In
comparison, Venezuela's costs are only 47 cents a lb and those in Canada are
51 cents.
Alumix, the state-owned Italian producer, recently announced a
rationalisation programme which will include the permanent closure in June
of the 30,000-tonnes-a-year Porto Maghera smelter.
The aluminium industry 'is closer to a shortage than a glut', says Anthony
Bird. 'We estimate that at the end of 1991 the margin of spare capacity and
the amount of excess stocks will be very similar to that seen in mid-1986 -
which was of course followed soon afterwards by a period of intense
shortage,' its latest Aluminium Analysis says.
Aluminium prices are 'dangerously low' because they make it impossible for
any new smelter project to cover its operating and capital costs and to earn
an acceptable profit, it says. 'That would call for a price of 77 to 83
cents a lb at April, 1991 prices and exchange rates.'
</TEXT>
