<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 91 / International Company News: Newmont Mining reveals 12% drop
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NEWMONT Mining, the US natural resources company in which financier Sir
James Goldsmith holds a 42 per cent stake, turned in a 12 per cent decline
in first-quarter net income from continuing operations on sales which fell 9
per cent.
For the three months ended March 31, Newmont recorded net income of Dollars
37.4m, or 55 cents a share, on sales of Dollars 151.3m, against Dollars
57.4m, or 85 cents, on sales of Dollars 165.5m a year ago. The 1990 earnings
were distorted by income from discontinued operations of Dollars 14.7m, or
22 cents a share, and a one-off after-tax gain of Dollars 10.4m, or 16
cents.
Net income from continuing operations was Dollars 37.4m in the 1991 quarter,
compared with Dollars 42.7m a year earlier.
During the first three months of 1991, the average price Newmont received
for gold fell to Dollars 401 an ounce from Dollars 414 an ounce a year
earlier.
Newmont Mining's 90.1 per cent interest in Newmont Gold contributed Dollars
36.2m in pre-tax income, down 23 per cent from Dollars 46.8m the year
before. Newmont Gold received an average of Dollars 373 an ounce for gold in
the latest quarter compared with Dollars 404 a year earlier.
Sir James acquired his holding in Newmont in October in a Dollars 1.3bn
forest-for-gold asset swap with Lord Hanson's UK conglomerate, in which Sir
James exchanged his stake in CFI - the major operating business within
Goldsmith's Oriental Investments group - for the Newmont holding.
</TEXT>
