<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 91 / UK Company News: N Brown placing as profits rise 12%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN THORNHILL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
N BROWN Group, the home shopping concern, joined the long list of companies
seeking funding from the stock market yesterday when it asked shareholders
for a net Pounds 16.4m to finance the development of a centralised warehouse
and distribution centre.
The placing and open offer, which represents the first time the company has
sought equity finance since 1971, is on a 1-for-8 basis at 209p per share.
The issue was well received in the City and the shares closed 3p higher at
228p.
Sir David Alliance, chairman, and his family trusts, have bought an
additional 1m shares in the company, taking their total holding to 65 per
cent, and have agreed to take up their full entitlement of shares under the
issue.
The balance has been conditionally placed with institutional investors by
Barclays de Zoete Wedd, subject to clawback from existing shareholders.
N Brown also brought forward its annual results yesterday to coincide with
the rights issue. These showed that pre-tax profits had advanced by 12 per
cent to Pounds 14.01m on sales of Pounds 140.17m (Pounds 126.57m).
Earnings per share rose from 13.95p to 15.67p and a final dividend of 4p is
recommended for a total of 5.65p, a 7.6 per cent increase.
The proceeds of the rights issue will help offset the Pounds 20m cost of
developing the company's warehouse at Shaw, near Manchester. By the end of
the year N Brown had already spent Pounds 18m on the project.
Following the rights issue, the company's gearing level will fall from 119
per cent to 56 per cent, helping to reduce its interest charge, which last
year amounted to Pounds 5.65m.
The company's core catalogues, targeted mainly at niche markets, were said
to have contributed a satisfactory performance. During the year N Brown also
launched another three catalogues including one for the disabled.
'There are 4m people from the wheelchair-bound to those with rheumatism who
are classified as disabled. The high street does not look after them so we
launched a catalogue for them,' said Mr Jim Martin, managing director.
He said he remained unconcerned by the recent consolidation of the UK mail
order industry which had seen Otto Versand, of Germany, snap up Grattan from
Next and Redoute Groupe, of France, buy Empire Stores Group. But he added
that in due course N Brown would look to develop its presence in continental
Europe.
</TEXT>
