<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 91 / Arts: On Wenlock Edge - Purcell Room
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD FAIRMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The poetry of Housman inspired a whole generation of song composers in this
country, Vaughan Williams being only the most considerable of them. His
cycle On Wenlock Edge is one of the important staging-posts in the evolution
of English song and the prospect of a leading tenor taking it on always
raises hopes.
On Wednesday the singer was Arthur Davies, well-known to audiences at
English National Opera and increasingly on the international stage. His is
an operatic tenor, clear and open in the Welsh tradition. He would probably
be happier singing this cycle with orchestra, as he is not an intimate song
interpreter in the line of Partridge or Rolfe-Johnson; but a little poetry
in his art would undoubtably shine through in the right performance.
Unfortunately the accompaniment was far too heavy; whether through lack of
rehearsal or a belief that they had a big operatic voice to support, the
London Smetana Trio (with extra violin and viola) played several notches too
loudly. That special feeling of a land eternal and tranquil, the heart of
what On Wenlock Edge is all about, was almost wholly lacking.
Almost, because it surfaced in the penultimate song, 'Bredon Hill'. At last
the playing became quiet. We could hear the words for the first time and the
sensitivity with which Davies charted the song's progress from lazy
summertime love to the chill bereavement of winter gave an idea of the
English song interpreter he might aspire to.
There are few song cycles written for piano quintet accompaniment and it was
enterprising of the performers to couple the Vaughan Williams with the first
performance of Marjolijn Anstey's The Lost Summer: Dunkirk 1940, a cantata
based on poems by Ted Harriott. This offers few opportunities for the singer
to show an awareness either of drama or poetry. But Davies's versatile
singing was a reminder of what a valuable tenor he has become to us.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
