<DATE>910426
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 91 / Arts: A city with a silver lining - The Museum of Walloon
Art, Liege
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICIA MORISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Lovers of fine silver quiver at the mention of Liege, the lovely but
much-ravaged city which bestrides the River Meuse. In the middle ages, along
the length of the Meuse there were towns and monasteries famous for
metal-working. The latest flowering of that tradition was the beautiful
17th- and 18th-century silverware of Liege, worthy to rank with the finest
in Europe.
This vanished craft has inspired an important exhibition at the Museum of
Walloon Art in Liege (until June 2). Domestic Silver of the Province of
Liege may not the most alluring of titles. However, this major exhibition
sponsored by Banque IPPA, is something of which Walloon patriots can feel
justly proud.
There has been some highly effective string-pulling behind this exhibition.
Of the 300 or so exhibits, a remarkable two-thirds come from the private
collections of old and unnamed Liegois families. Since it has never been
shown in public nor even published, the experts and dealers are not going to
want to miss such a golden opportunity.
They will also appreciate the exceptionally handsome and scholarly catalogue
(BF 950); it is also, I might add, dry-as-dust. It gives a complete
directory of Liege hallmarks, with the wry comment that it will be a great
help to silver fakers. A few examples of fake pieces have been included in
the show, their modern origin detected because of misunderstood hallmarks.
However, the fake can also be detected thanks to recent research into the
kind of alloy used in Liege, mid-way in quality between Bavaria and Paris.
For the low-brow silver enthusiast, however, the exhibition offers the
pleasure of a vast and varied hoard of covetable objects, ranging from
coffee-pots and candle-snuffers to sword-hilts, cake-slices, and a
clothes-brush. A short didactic section describes the workings of the
all-powerful guild of silversmiths. However, the kind of detailed
information about craftsmen, their workshops and customers which makes
students of the London silver trade so happy, is missing. When the French
army took Liege in 1794 and, horrible deed, burnt the vast cathedral of St
Lambert, they also abolished the guilds and the archives vanished.
Liege in the Ancien Regime was an unusual place. It was the capital of a
principality ruled, as it had been since the days of the great Bishop Notker
in the 10th century, by a Prince-Bishop. And that, we are told with rather
tantalising brevity, accounts for the style of Liege silver. No king meant
no vying to impress foreign diplomats and hostile powers, no posturing noble
courtiers. It meant no Madame de Pompadour, no Madame de Montespan. The
Church dominated life in the city; when the bishop died, they changed the
hall-marks.
Customers for new silver and those who equally often took heirlooms along to
be refashioned, were either clerics or sober-sided bourgeois. Some
impression of the social setting comes from a reproduction of a painting by
the 18th-century artist, Paul-Joseph Delcloche. It shows the bishop and his
dinner-guests supping off oysters. There is plenty of silver about the room
and on the table, but by far the richest object is the jewelled crucifix on
the episcopal midriff.
So Liege silverware tends to be elegant and unostentatious, whether the
pieces are Baroque, Rococo or influenced by the new classicism which creeps
in from around 1750. Generally, fashion tends to be ten years behind Paris
and London. On the other hand, in terms of technique masterpieces were
produced to match anything which could be brought at more metropolitan
centres. Not all the exhibits come from Liege; there is a group of objects
from the so-called bonnes villes of the province, such as Maastricht,
Waremme and Saint-Trond.
Splendid table fountains, containing no one know quite what, were a
particular feature of the Low Countries and there are many in the show,
majestically pear-shaped on three legs. Many coffee-pots and candlesticks of
the 1770s have a violently twisted, swirling form which reminds us that art
nouveau was later to flower spectacularly in Belgium.
Centre-piece of the exhibition is an elegant table laid for a six o'clock
dinner for eight persons. The date would seem to be sometime round the
1780s, last years of the good life in rich, tasteful, independent Liege.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 21 Photograph A 'fontaine de table' attributed to Bastin
Martini, 1738-1739, marque, George-Louis de Berghes (Omitted).
</PAGE>
