FT  26 APR 91 / UK News (Employment): Teachers will reserve option of
striking
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE National Union of Teachers, the largest teaching union, yesterday backed
away from strike action in opposition to the government's review body for
teachers' pay. However, its executive reaffirmed the union's opposition to
the body and refused to rule out the use of future industrial action.
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the education secretary, last week made the setting-up of
the review body conditional upon the unions 'tacitly' giving up the strike
weapon. In spite of the NUT's stance, he is still proceeding with the
Teacher's Pay Bill, which has its second reading in the Commons on Monday.
Mr Doug McAvoy, NUT general secretary, said yesterday: 'Teachers should fear
a review body because it could lead to a longer working year, a reduction in
teacher support time, an extension of their duties and responsibilities, and
increased use of discretionary pay, causing further divisions in the
teaching profession.'
However, the union said the NUT would take part in the review, if
established, and indicated that strike action on the issue was now highly
unlikely. The other five teachers' unions all support the proposed review
body.
The NUT also decided yesterday to oppose the introduction of teacher
appraisal unless the government withdraws its proposal to link it to
discretionary pay awards. Graduates are in increasing proportion taking a
year out before starting work, a report disclosed yesterday. Cambridge
University careers service said that 12 per cent of graduates were still not
looking for work six months after graduation. Of those proceeding to jobs,
teaching and the law were the most popular choices.
</TEXT>
