<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 91 / Parliament and Politics: Unease surfaces over fairness of
local tax - Council finance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR John Major insisted yesterday in the face of some Tory expressions of
unease, that the government's plans for a council tax would be fair and that
more than 70 per cent of people would gain from the change.
Labour MPs cheered as Mr Peter Fry, Tory MP for Wellingborough, warned that
there would have to be an investigation into the disadvantage suffered by
his local authority if he were to advise his constituents that the tax was
fair.
Wellingborough had been penalised for trading profitably and passing the
profits on to chargepayers, he said in the Commons, and even the cheapest
house there would pay more than the dearest house in Westminster.
There would also be a transitional protection scheme and rebates for people
on low incomes.
The plans came under a further Tory attack, when Miss Beryl Goldsmith,
secretary to Mr Norman Tebbit, condemned them as 'grossly inequitable.'
Miss Goldsmith, in a letter to the London Evening Standard, made it clear
that her letter had nothing to do with Mr Tebbit.
Her complaint, raised with Mr Major by a Labour MP, was that even after the
discount for someone living alone, her one-living-room flat in the Barbican
would attract a higher bill than that for Mr Michael Heseltine, the
environment secretary, and his family, in Westminster.
Mr Chris Patten, the Tory party chairman, and Mr Heseltine both emphasised
that the surest way to reduce local tax bills was to vote Tory.
Speaking in Bristol, Mr Patten said that residents there faced 'double
jeopardy' from coming under a Labour-controlled city and county.
A Labour government committed to scrapping the government's powers to cap
council spending would mean 'triple jeopardy,' he said.
Labour, meanwhile, renewed a broad attack on the Tories' approach to local
government, saying that the choice in the May elections was between 'quality
and cuts' in services such as transport and education.
While maintaining the attack on the council tax, Mr John Cunningham, the
party's campaign co-ordinator, refused to commit the party to repealing
council tax legislation if it were passed before the election, saying he
thought the timetable unlikely to be achieved.
As for charges of high-spending, Labour pledged that its Quality Commission
would mean efficient delivery of local services, and challenged the
government to say why people should not be able to vote for a higher level
of service.
Government spending on advertising has increased as the local elections have
approached, as it did before the 1987 local elections, according to a study
commissioned by BBC Radio.
Out of an advertising spend of Pounds 34m in the first three months of the
year, nearly half was spent in March.
