<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 91 / The Guinness Appeals: Decision may take two weeks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND HUGHES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Ernest Saunders, Mr Anthony Parnes and Mr Gerald Ronson must wait another
two to three weeks before learning whether they have won their appeals
against their convictions in the Guinness trial.
The Court of Appeal yesterday finished hearing the appeals, which Lord
Justice Neill said raised important and difficult issues. He said it would
be at least a fortnight before he and Mr Justice Ognall and Mr Justice Owen
would be able to give their judgment. If they dismiss the appeals against
conviction, they will go on to hear appeals against the sentences imposed on
the three men at the end of the trial last August.
Mr Saunders, the former Guinness chairman and chief executive, is serving
five years for conspiracy, theft and false accounting.
Mr Parnes, a City stockbroker, was sentenced to 2 1/2 years for theft and
false accounting.
Mr Ronson, head of the Heron group, released in February after serving just
under half his 12-month jail term, was also fined a record Pounds 5m on his
convictions of conspiracy, theft and false accounting.
He had been given until May 25 to pay the fine. Yesterday the Appeal Court
extended the time until 10 days after the end of the appeals.
Mr Saunders and Mr Parnes are in Ford open prison in West Sussex. If their
appeals fail, Mr Parnes will be eligible for parole at the end of June and
Mr Saunders at the end of next April.
The central issue in the appeals against conviction, which lasted eight
days, has been the defence contention that Mr Justice Henry, the trial
judge, misdirected the jury.
All the charges in the case related to the share support operation mounted
by Guinness during the takeover battle for Distillers.
</TEXT>
