<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 91 / Too soon for links with Nato
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT MAUTHNER, Diplomatic Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The new democracies of central and eastern Europe, such as Hungary and
Czechoslovakia could not, for the moment, expect to establish formal
membership links with Nato, Mr Manfred Worner, Nato secretary-general said
in Prague yesterday, writes Robert Mauthner, diplomatic correspondent.
Mr Worner told a conference on the future of European security that Nato did
not seek a shift of balance or an extension of military borders to the east,
nor could it provide former members of the Warsaw Pact with formal security
guarantees.
'At the moment, what Nato can offer is a multiple and intensive web of
relations which does not exclude the Soviet Union, but wants it to be a
constructive and creative partner as well.'
</TEXT>
