<HEADLINE>
FT  26 APR 91 / (CORRECTED) UK Company News: Acorn Computer falls 38% to
Pounds 1.58m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Correction (published 27th April 1991) appended to this article.
CONFUSION OVER new legislation concerning school management and uncertainty
over the effects of the community charge have combined to take the shine off
1990 results at Acorn Computer.
Turnover at Pounds 45.5m was marginally up on the Pounds 44.9m recorded the
previous year, while pre-tax profits fell from Pounds 2.53m in 1989 to
Pounds 1.58m in 1990, a fall of 38 per cent. Earnings per ordinary share
declined to 2.4p (3.8p).
Acorn, based in Cambridge and in which Olivetti of Italy has a majority
shareholding, is a main supplier of school computers, reckoning to have at
least one of its machines in 85 per cent of junior and secondary schools.
Purchasing patterns in schools have changed as a result of the introduction
of local management, and uncertainties over the level of funds available
because of the introduction of the community charge have slowed spending in
what is usually an unspectacular but reliable sector.
Acorn's operating profits last year rose to Pounds 2m compared with Pounds
1.3m in 1989. However, the company sold intellectual property rights in its
advanced reduced instruction set processor chips for Pounds 1.5m to a new
company established between Acorn, Apple Computer and LSI Logic of the US.
In 1990 the company also made provision of Pounds 900,000 against bad debts
due from a customer, resulting in a net exceptional profit of Pounds
561,000.
For the 1989 year the company recorded an exceptional profit of Pounds 1.2m
through selling an option on sales and marketing rights to a particular
product to Olivetti.
Interest charges accounted for Pounds 995,000 in 1990 compared with previous
income of Pounds 9,000 reflecting increases in working capital as the
recession in the latter part of the year began to have an effect.
The directors said that 53 per cent of all computers delivered to UK schools
in 1990 were Acorn, with the new BBC A3000 and Archimedes machines
outselling the earlier technology Master series by two to one.
Correction (published 27th April 1991).
VLSI, US-based semiconductor supplier, is the third partner in a new company
set up with microcomputer companies Acorn and Apple and not LSI Logic as
reported yesterday.
</TEXT>
