<HEADLINE>
FT  25 APR 91 / Laura Ashley losses jump to Pounds 6.7m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN THORNHILL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LAURA ASHLEY, the fashion and furnishings group, yesterday announced
steepening pre-tax losses to Pounds 6.67m in the year to January 26, from
Pounds 1.58m.
However, Mr Mike Smith, acting chief executive, said Laura Ashley had
achieved its main objective to strengthen its balance sheet. 'This was a
year of restructuring, rather than profit,' he said.
Earlier in the year the company was involved in a refinancing. It later
restructured by closing seven factories and its Units retailing chain,
selling its Penhaligon, Bryants, Sandringham Leather and Helmond Printworks
businesses, and cutting overheads.
Laura Ashley also announced a trading link with Aeon Group which resulted in
the Japanese retailer taking a stake.
The rationalisation resulted in borrowings falling to Pounds 23m from Pounds
87m, reducing gearing to 25 per cent from 119 per cent. The disposals and
tighter management controls helped cut stock levels by 38 per cent by the
year end.
Laura Ashley increased sales 10 per cent to Pounds 327.53m but higher costs
and an increased interest charge of Pounds 12.44m, against Pounds 8.64m,
eroded gains.
UK turnover grew to Pounds 143.6m from Pounds 142.6m, although the overall
figure concealed a 4.1 per cent decline in like-for-like sales. Home
furnishing sales remained flat because of the depressed housing market and
garment sales fell as the recession bit.
The company's international operations were more resilient. North American
outlets increased their sales contribution to Pounds 136.2m from Pounds
117.2m, although margins were held back by discounting.
Sales in continental Europe were also strongly ahead at Pounds 40.7m,
against Pounds 28.6m, and the link with Aeon led to the opening of 13 shops
in Japan and an 88 per cent sales boost.
Losses per share amounted to 2.6p compared with losses of 3.38p in the
previous period.
The company is paying a nominal final dividend of 0.1p although directors
and the Ashley family are waiving their entitlements.
The company is reviewing its marketing and has appointed Ms Glenne Gibson
from Coopers &amp; Lybrand Deloitte to help develop the international brand. She
said this would lead to designs reflecting consumer aspirations through the
1990s. 'But we will not be phasing out all our flowers,' she said yesterday.
Laura Ashley expects to appoint a chief executive soon after receiving 500
applications.
Lex, Page 22; Aquascutum chief retires, Page 25
</TEXT>
