<HEADLINE>
FT  25 APR 91 / Activity on USM dries up in first quarter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLARE PEARSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FOR the first time in more than 10 years, no companies chose to raise funds
by joining the Unlisted Securities Market during the first quarter.
The drying up of activity is revealed in new-issue statistics published
yesterday by accountants KPMG Peat Marwick McLintock. KPMG monitors new
issues on both the USM and the stock exchange's official list.
New-issue activity on both markets was severely depressed during the
quarter, largely due to the UK recession and uncertainties after the Gulf
war.
The statistics also revealed a new low in the steady, steep decline of
companies seeking a USM quotation. The junior market, founded in November
1980, was once a bustling arena for the small and growing company.
Last year, the number of new issues was 47, raising a total of Pounds 40m
worth of new money, down from 87 raising Pounds 303m in 1988.
Some followers of the USM are concerned that its relative decline will
continue, even when investor appetite for new issues improves. Changes in
stock exchange regulations have made it easier for companies to go straight
to the official list.
The first-quarter statistics continue last year's trend. KPMG said the USM
last year suffered a net shrinkage as 29 of its constituent companies moved
up to the main market.
The figures show that the main market saw 12 new entrants. Three of these
were investment trusts which raised funds when they floated. But all nine
companies joining the market came by way of introduction, where a listing is
obtained without shares being simultaneously sold.
The investment trusts raised a total of Pounds 90m in the first quarter. New
entrants to the main market in 1990 raised Pounds 899m.
The comparative figures exclude privatisations, including this spring's
flotation of National Power and PowerGen, the two electricity generators.
Meanwhile, five companies obtained a USM quotation during the first three
months  - the lowest-ever quarterly total. All of these were introductions
and three were transfers from the Third Market  - the arena for the very
smallest and youngest companies which was abolished at the beginning of the
year.
Six of the companies introduced to the official list came from the USM.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
