<HEADLINE>
FT  25 APR 91 / Parliament and Politics: PM braces himself for a year of
living dangerously - Political Notebook
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IT is not hard to see why John Major wants to avoid postponing the general
election until 1992. The charge of ditherer might stick. The winter and
spring would be dominated by messy legislation to introduce the council tax.
Europe could yet re-emerge as a dangerously divisive issue. Then, of course,
there is the unpredictable.
So the emerging consensus in the cabinet is that Mr Major will seek his
mandate in the Autumn. Some ministers are convinced there is a chance still
of a late June election. With the poll tax cauterised, they argue, the
Tories might yet do well in the May 2 local elections. If they then held
Monmouth in the by-election two weeks later, the stage could be set to
secure a 50-seat Westminster majority before the voters departed for the
Costa del Sol.
For most though, October or November looks by far the stronger bet. The
Treasury judgment is that the promise of better times ahead is not enough.
The electorate needs to feel the benefit of lower inflation and mortgage
rates for a few months before they will forgive the government its past
economic sins.
Unemployment will get a lot worse before it even starts to get better. Many
C2 voters whose mood will determine the election have already decided that
this year they will have to forsake Benidorm for Bognor. There is still a
lobby in Great George Street for 1992.
That said, the mood in the Cabinet is remarkably buoyant  - at times almost
complacent. It is partly because his colleagues like Mr Major's style. To
some, cabinet government may look like dithering; to insiders it is what one
likes to refer to as a 'gale of fresh air.' If polls are a guide, the voters
agree.
Ministers believe the government has absorbed not only everything it has
thrown at itself but also the best Labour can muster. The parties are neck
and neck now, but every extra point off mortgage rates should put two or
three points on the Tories' rating.
There is another reason why the prime minister will want to avoid soldiering
on until the bitter end. It is invariably overlooked.
The approaching public spending round is about to provide the first real
test of 'Majorism'. It will tell us whether he can, as promised, be tougher
than Mrs Thatcher on inflation, still deliver tax cuts, and yet give the
public sector enough money to provide a decent standard of services.
He could not have chosen a tougher year to try to square the circle. The
detailed figures, as always, are obscure, the more so because the switch
from local taxation to VAT has distorted the Treasury's cash planning
totals.
But the bottom line could not be more painfully clear. The rising
unemployment which comes with economic recession alongside public sector
wage deals reflecting last year's rather than this year's inflation rates
have wiped out most of the real growth built into the 1990 public spending
settlement.
The latest spending round  - its start has just been signalled by a lengthy
and gloomy Treasury sent to all the main spending departments - will be even
tougher than the last.
Public sector pay settlements averaging 8 per cent have bitten deeply into
the Treasury's contingency reserve for the current financial year. So too
has the sharp rise in unemployment, the Budget concession on child benefit
and a commitment to spend more on training.
Inflation in 1992 will be lower, but every extra pound spent this year
raises the base lines on which spending ministers predicate their bids for
extra cash in 1992/93.
At the department of health Mr William Waldegrave, can argue that his cash
allocation for next year implies at best a freeze and at worst a real cut in
NHS spending. With the NHS reforms likely to make cash shortages more
transparent, we can expect him to bid for an extra Pounds 2bn or so.
Mr Kenneth Clarke, never shy about asking for an extra several billion will
make a similar case at education. Mr Major has promised after all to raise
the status (that means pay) of career teachers. On the most optimistic
assumptions Mr Michael Heseltine will need Pounds 1.5bn to prevent the final
year of the poll tax from turning 1992 into the final year of the
government. It is not difficult to double that.
Back at the Treasury Mr Norman Lamont is looking at a forecast Pounds 8bn
budget deficit which already looks optimistic. And he would, as he reminded
us the ther day, at least make a start on cutting taxes.
It is the sort of circle that Mr Major would do best to try squaring after
and not before a general election.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
