<HEADLINE>
FT  25 APR 91 / Government Bonds: Strong demand pushes gilt auction to
success
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SARA WEBB and PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Bank of England's first gilt auction in nearly three years was hailed as
a resounding success yesterday. The full amount of Pounds 1.2bn of 10 per
cent Conversion stock 1996 was gobbled up by the market amid signs of strong
demand for the stock.
The Bank of England received bids of Pounds 5.375bn for a total of Pounds
1.2bn in stock, so the issue was covered 4.45 times.
The highest accepted bid was Pounds 98 21/32 , corresponding to a yield of
10.32 per cent, while the lowest accepted bid was for Pounds 98 17/32 ,
corresponding to a yield of 10.35 per cent. The rounded average accepted
price was Pounds 98 9/16 , corresponding to a yield of 10.34 per cent.
Traders said the short 'tail' and the high cover were signs that the auction
was a roaring success. The tail - which is the difference between the
average yield and the yield corresponding to the lowest price - was only one
basis point.
The Bank of England said bids at the lowest accepted price were allotted
46.5 per cent of the amount for which they applied.
The when-issued stock opened at Pounds 48 5/8 , only a couple of ticks above
the average bid price when bidding took place, and was trading at Pounds 48
3/4 by late morning, equivalent to a fully paid-up price of Pounds 98 3/4 .
Demand came mainly from domestic buyers, traders said.
The Bank of England is expected to hold a further two or three auctions this
year.
Otherwise, the gilts market drifted up during the day, but volumes were low.
German bund prices edged up in the morning but slipped back again later.
A statement from Bundesbank board member Mr Otmar Issing, quoted in a German
magazine, did little to reassure the market. Mr Issing said the Bundesbank
would do everything it could to keep the D-Mark stable, but recognised that
the impact of foreign exchange intervention was limited.
Yesterday's auction of Japanese Government Bonds was well received, dealers
said. The auction was for Y800bn of the No 140 ten-year bond with a coupon
of 6.6 per cent. The average price was 100.38, corresponding to a yield of
6.537 per cent while the lowest accepted bid was for 100.30, corresponding
to a yield of 6.55 per cent. The short tail was seen as a sign of strong
retail demand, traders said.
Otherwise, prices in the market slipped during the day with the yield on the
benchmark No 129 bond moving from 6.7 per cent in the morning to close at
6.74 per cent.
US government bond prices firmed in late trading yesterday following a
successful auction of two-year notes and some weak car sales figures from US
manufacturers.
By late afternoon the benchmark 30-year Treasury issue was up  19/32 at 96
3/16 , to yield 8.212 per cent, while the two year note was up  1/8 at 100
9/32 , carrying a yield of 6.946 per cent.
Although there were some worries over the market's ability to absorb the
additional supply in the two-year note auction, the sale passed off
smoothly.
The market was also buoyed by the mid-April car sales figures from the
country's big makers. Analysts were looking for the figures to show annual
sales running at 6m cars, up from 5.6m in early April, and based on initial
reports from General Motors and Ford, sales in the period were below that.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
