FT  25 APR 91 / UK News (Employment): Short-time work takes bigger toll
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NUMBER of hours lost through short-time working has doubled over the
past year as organisations attempt to hold on to skilled employees during
the recession rather than make them redundant, according to a study
published today.
In January 1991, more than half a million hours a week were lost where
employees were stood off for the whole or part of a week. That was double
the number of hours lost in January 1990, although still far short of levels
reached during the recession of the early 1980s, says the research group
Incomes Data Services.
The study says: 'Many employers are only too aware of the recent
difficulties they experienced in attempting to recruit and retain skilled
employees and they are reluctant to lose these people.'
Short-time working is widespread in sectors such as textiles, footwear and
clothing, and motor vehicles. Service industries such as travel have also
been affected.
Lay-Offs and Short-Time Working. Available to subscribers from IDS, 193 St
John St, London, EC1V 4LS.
</TEXT>
