<HEADLINE>
FT  25 APR 91 / UK News (Employment): Unions agree to back TUC on pay
bargaining
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TRADE UNION leaders yesterday put aside differences on a pay bargaining
structure under a future Labour government and agreed a common public line.
The compromise was formulated in spite of some strong doubts about the
proposed system.
The general council of the Trades Union Congress unanimously approved a
paper outlining plans for a system, including a national economic assessment
and a national minimum wage, after making alterations to accommodate
concerns of the AEU engineering union that pay differentials might be
eroded.
Potential difficulties in achieving a consensus on the issue were
highlighted yesterday when the AEU's national committee, meeting in
Eastbourne, approved a motion that noted 'with concern attempts to suppress
free collective bargaining with a national wages assessment and similar
devices'.
Mr Alan Tuffin, general secretary of the UCW postal workers' union and a
strong supporter of the co-ordinated bargaining advocated in the TUC
document, admitted there could be difficulties in the future.
He said: 'Problems associated with a minimum wage and a national economic
assessment do not sit comfortably with free collective bargaining if that
mean a wages free-for-all.'
The twice revised TUC document repeatedly rejects the notion of pay norms or
pay restraint. Even so, concern continues that a national assessment,
involving trade unions, employers and government, might lead to restraint.
From the AEU's point of view, one of the most crucial changes was to clauses
involving a minimum wage.
After the revision, the document says: 'Such increases shall not inhibit
free collective bargaining or prevent the appropriate rate for the job being
negotiated by trade unions.'
It adds: 'Any exceptional increase given solely for the purpose of
implementing the provisions of statutory minimum pay legislation will not be
regarded by trade unions as a vehicle for general increases.'
</TEXT>
