<HEADLINE>
FT  25 APR 91 / UK News (Employment): Anger over government challenge - How
unions view their Civil Service pay offer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THIS year the government's side in pay talks with the two largest groups of
civil servants was led by two people new to salary negotiations. If the
unions hoped for an easy time through their opponents' inexperience,
however, they have been disappointed.
Ms Gillian Shephard, minister of state at the Treasury, and Ms Anthea Case,
senior civil servant, pitched an offer low enough to provoke the first
significant challenge to long-term pay agreements since they were introduced
into the Civil Service four years ago.
The challenge arose from union perceptions that the 8 per cent pay offer
breaks the spirit of the long-term agreements. It was probably not unwelcome
to a government keen to show the private sector how to conclude low pay
deals but severely constrained in its ability to do so this year because of
clauses in the deals.
The problem for the leaderships of the CPSA and NUCPS unions is that the
offer does not break the letter of the long-term agreements. They were
therefore faced with recommending acceptance of the 8 per cent offer, or
moving towards industrial action which they knew their members were
reluctant to take. The CPSA executive this week decided on acceptance; the
NUCPS recommended rejection, with the possibility of a ballot on industrial
action.
Whatever the result of that ballot, the unions' hostile response has
deflected attention from the potentially embarrassing fact that the 8 per
cent offer could be interpreted as inflationary. The retail prices index is
expected to fall to below 7 per cent this month; the offer is due for
implementation from April 1.
An inflation-plus deal does not look good for a government that is
constantly preaching that employers should make 'affordable' pay rises,
interpreted by most as meaning below inflation.
The government has not escaped without criticism. Shortly after the offer
was announced, Mr John Banham, director-general of the Confederation of
British Industry, observed that public pay was rising too fast, threatening
'further essential cuts in interest rates'. But the criticisms would have
been worse without the public controversy over the offers.
In the Civil Service negotiations, the government's hand was forced by the
long-term pay agreements through which rises are linked to increases in the
private sector. The Civil Service rises must fall in the middle 50 per cent
of the private sector increases during the previous year.
Rising inflation works to the government's benefit because private sector
earnings tend to track the retail prices index. As inflation falls, as now,
the opposite occurs and the Treasury's comparability concessions cause
difficulties.
The advantage for the government of the long-term deal is that the unions
have allowed the Treasury more flexibility in where to target money. In the
first years of the deals, high performing civil servants in London - where
recruitment and retention were most difficult - were awarded higher rises
than others.
This year the high rises have been targeted at the low-paid who have won up
to 11 per cent. Most of the more than 300,000 civil servants covered by the
offers will receive between 7.6 per cent and 7.8 per cent.
That is what has angered the unions who say the long-term agreements would
only be honoured in spirit if all members were offered at least 8 per cent,
the lowest point of the middle 50 per cent in the private sector.
In spite of their annoyance, there is little support among the two unions'
leaderships for pulling out of the agreements.
Mr John Ellis, CPSA general secretary, said yesterday that the agreements
have stabilised industrial relations in the Civil Service, making strikes
such as those staged in 1981 and 1987 less likely. Until this year they have
also provided fair increases, he says.
He estimates that without the long-term agreements, this year's offer would
only have been about 6 per cent. His union will push for changes to the
agreements, for example to make more use of arbitration.
The NUCPS, the most reluctant of the Civil Service unions to join the
long-term agreements, is less positive about them. It is not hostile,
however, and its leadership will argue against withdrawal at this year's
annual conference.
Significantly, the union's executive did not this week order an immediate
ballot on industrial action. That would only come if members supported the
rejection recommendation and the government continued to reject arbitration.
That means industrial action can be virtually ruled out. A ballot may
eventually be held on industrial action, but it will come at a time when the
inflation rate is considerably less than the value of the offer. In a
recession, when hundreds of thousands of workers are being made redundant,
few workers would strike for an improvement to an inflation-plus offer.
</TEXT>
