<HEADLINE>
FT  25 APR 91 / Parliament and Politics: Anxieties over tight timetabling -
Local Taxation Reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD EVANS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PROPERTY valuation experts confirmed yesterday that there should be no
insuperable barrier to banding all 22m homes in Britain prior to introducing
the proposed successor to the poll tax.
However, anxieties were expressed over the tight timetable if the new
council tax is to be introduced by April, 1993, and over some details which
have clearly not yet been considered fully.
There was relief in the valuation profession that ministers had decided in
favour of a rating system based on capital values, rather than returning to
the old, discredited system of rental values or recommending site valuation.
The essential point is that the chosen method does not entail a property by
property valuation, but simply the allocation of each property to one of the
proposed bands.
In most cases this should present no difficulty, as the old rating lists and
valuations have been retained and were updated until the introduction of the
poll tax last year. There is also a wealth of additional information from
local property sales.
'The basic prescription of 22m homes allocated to seven bands is sensible
and, for 90 per cent of properties, readily achievable,' said Mr Michael
Pattison, secretary general of the Royal Institution of Chartered Surveyors.
Mr Charles Partridge of Herring Son &amp; Daw, the chartered surveyors, said:
'It is the ideal approach because everyone understands capital values, and
putting each property into a broad band is not a difficult job.'
The Inland Revenue's valuation office will be responsible for allocating
each property to one of the seven bands, which in England will range from up
to Pounds 40,000 to over Pounds 160,000, with lower levels operating in
Scotland and Wales.
But because its resources are already fully stretched by appeals against
uniform business rate demands, much of the work is certain to be contracted
out to private sector professionals.
According to the RICS, the government could adopt a 'beacon' system of
valuation under which a typical property would be chosen as the basis of
valuation for similar properties in the same area.
A terrace house, for example, could be used to provide a representative
value for all properties in the same terrace, and in some cases whole areas
could be valued in this way.
The assumption is that most householders would be likely to accept the
banding decisions, which because of the amount of information available,
should be consistent with their own views on the market value of their
homes.
This method of valuation would be a rough and ready means of valuation and
so a right of appeal will be vital.
Problems arise at the margin of each band and at the precise point in a
street or estate where the properties have been allocated to the next band.
Mr Pattison forecast that in some cases there could be agitation to get a
property or housing estate into a higher band, despite the cost, because of
the extra social cachet this could provide.
Unlike the rating system, home improvements will not automatically mean a
change of band, and any alterations might only be taken into account when a
property changes hands.
Among questions still to be answered are whether leasehold properties will
be valued at their freehold value; how will 'unorthodox' types of property
such as caravans and houseboats be treated; and will banding be subject to
some form of indexation.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
