FT  25 APR 91 / Parliament and Politics: Major proposes UN arms register
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PLANS for establishing a United Nations arms register to provide an early
warning system of countries building up excessive arms stockpiles, were
spelt out by Mr John Major, the prime minister, yesterday, Alison Smith
writes.
In an interview on Sky news, Mr Major said the register would rely the
registration of arms sales by the suppliers. 85 per cent of arms
predominately come from the five permanent members of the UN security
council.
The idea should be considered at the UN and at the Group of Seven economic
summit in the summer, he said.
He acknowledged that the ability to purchase arms through third parties
meant that it would not be a perfect solution.
Even so, it would 'focus minds on the difficulties that arise when there are
too many armaments in too confined a space and in unsafe hands.'
Asked about the future of the Kurds, he said that there must be certainty
that the safe havens were not used as a jumping off point for incursions
into Iraq, but that the immediate question was getting them to come down
from the mountains. Questioned about the allies' attitude to co-operation
from the Iraqi government, he confirmed he still believed that while Saddam
Hussein remained in power, Iraq would be 'a pariah.'
The Ministry of Defence admitted yesterday that Britain will have no
frontline ground-to-air missile defences against enemy aircraft attacks for
four years, after the current medium-range Bloodhound missiles are phased
out this year. A replacement would not be ready until the middle of the
decade, officials said.
</TEXT>
