<HEADLINE>
FT  25 APR 91 / Parliament and Politics: Labour challenges tax figures -
Local Taxation Reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR yesterday began a two-pronged attack on the government's council tax
figures, both challenging their basis and saying that they showed average
households would do better under Labour's plans for 'fair rates'.
Mr Bryan Gould, the shadow environment spokesman, said: 'These figures
conclusively prove that most people will be better off under Labour's fair
rate scheme.'
At the same time, he recalled that the original estimates for average poll
tax bills had been Pounds 178, later revised upwards to Pounds 278, while
the average bill last year was Pounds 357.
Similar revisions of council tax bill estimates, he added, would mean
average household bills of Pounds 802.
While such claims are a legitimate part of the numbers game being played by
the main parties, they do not help in a comparison of the figures for
average household bills under a council tax or rates.
For politicians attacking each other's calculations, Labour and Tories share
a surprising number of assumptions on their way to average household bills
of Pounds 333 and Pounds 360 respectively. Both take as their basis the
inclusion of the community charge reduction scheme with the revenue support
grant (although Labour counts it as about Pounds 1bn while the Tories count
it as Pounds 1.25bn); both assume that collection will be much better than
for the poll tax (the Tories calculating on 100 per cent collection and
Labour on 98 per cent - as it was under the rates); and both assume
significant savings on collection costs (Labour of Pounds 400,000 and the
Tories of Pounds 320,000).
Both parties also compare the new system with headline poll tax figures this
year given actual council spending, and no increase in the total from the
business rate.
Labour's attack on the figures will include sustained questioning of the
valuation which formed the basis of the property profile given for each
area.
Party officials doubt that sampling will have been extensive and describe
the exercise as 'pretty spurious'.
Mr Michael Portillo, the local government minister, ascribed the difference
in average household figures to the fact that Labour was aiming to raise
only Pounds 6.3bn from local taxes instead of the Pounds 6.8bn government
figures represented.
Tory officials also say the Pounds 400 average household figure is based on
the median house price, reflecting the range of council tax bills to be
paid. Labour's refusal to give details of distribution of bills under its
proposals means that there is no directly comparable figure for the
opposition's system.
Labour offers a different explanation. It says the limit on top band
contributions in the council tax and the 25 per cent discount for
single-person households means that to compensate, the average household
pays more than if the tax were fully progressive.
It agrees, however, that it assumes greater savings from the higher
collection rate than the government is doing - a point where independent
experts thought they had overestimated by Pounds 600,000 - but adds that the
same experts agreed with their conclusions of a Pounds 140 savings for an
average household.
Mr David Blunkett, the opposition local-government spokesman, said: 'Our
figures are robust, real and verified by independent analysts. Their figures
are a fairy tale without a happy ending.'
The ending to both stories looks likely to come only after the general
election.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
