FT  25 APR 91 / Parliament and Politics: Authorities still hazy over review
 -Local Taxation Reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ALTHOUGH the government's proposals for the new council tax are well
documented in its consultation paper, details of how the review of local
government will be carried out remained hazy yesterday.
Officials of the Associations of District Councils, County Councils and
Metropolitan Authorities met Mr Michael Heseltine, the environment
secretary, yesterday for an hour-long briefing, but said little detail had
emerged beyond what was published in the government's consultation paper on
the structure of local government on Tuesday.
Mr Roy Thomason, chairman of the Association of District Councils, which
welcomed the government's announcement that it intended to move towards more
unitary authorities in England, said it was unlikely that the proposed Local
Government Commission would be set up until after the second reading of the
bill. Depending on whether there is a general election, that is likely to be
early in the next session of parliament in the autumn.
He said the local-authority associations had made clear to Mr Heseltine that
they felt they should be closely consulted about the composition of the
commission.
It is not known how many members the commission will have, or who will chair
it.
According to the consultation paper, the review commission will take over
the functions of the Local Government Boundary Commission. Mr Thomason said
he had proposed that the Boundary Commission should suspend making any new
decisions that might affect the local-government review until the review
body has been set up.
Plans for the local-government review seem to be considerably less advanced
than those for the council tax, and the Department of the Environment
emphasised yesterday that it was keen to hear the views of authorities
before proceeding further. Councils have been invited to put their views to
the DoE by June 14.
</TEXT>
