<HEADLINE>
FT  25 APR 91 / Parliament and Politics: Half of electorate found to support
system of PR - Electoral Reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HALF the electorate favours the replacement of Britain's first-past-the-post
voting system by proportional representation, according to a 'state of the
nation' survey published yesterday.
Pressure on Mr Neil Kinnock and his shadow cabinet to back the change will
be intensified by the disclosure that it would be approved by more than a
two-to-one majority among Labour Party supporters.
The survey, commissioned by the Rowntree Reform Trust and conducted by
Market &amp; Opinion Research International (Mori), also indicated that
Conservative voters were split almost evenly for and against the switch.
This is seen as reflecting a growing public perception of Mr John Major, the
prime minister, as a more consensual figure than Mrs Margaret Thatcher, his
predecessor, but will make little impact on the Conservative party's
traditional opposition to PR so long as it is able to command a majority in
the Commons at regular intervals.
Mr Robin Cook, principal health spokesman and leading advocate of the
abandonment of the first-past-the-post voting system in the Shadow Cabinet,
welcomed the verdict that Labour voters wanted PR even more strongly than
the rest of the population.
He emphasised: 'This poll shows Labour should stop resisting PR as a threat
and start to recognise it as an opportunity'.
Mr Cook's enthusiasm is unlikely to receive early public endorsement from Mr
Kinnock. The Labour leader, like the majority of his senior colleagues,
fears that a declaration of support for changing the voting system at the
present time would be interpreted as lack of confidence in the party's
prospects for forming a majority government after the next general election.
Even so, a resolution approved by last year's Labour conference requiring
the National Executive to consider alternatives to the first-past-the-post
voting system for elections to the House of Commons ensures that PR stays
high on the party's agenda.
Mr Robert Maclennan, home affairs spokesman for the Liberal Democrats - the
most consistent advocates of electoral reform among the leading political
parties - said the survey showed they were more in tune with public opinion
about how Britain was governed than any of their rivals.
Other findings from the survey are:
More than 50 per cent support fixed term parliaments, thus denying the prime
minister of the day the right to make party advantage the first
consideration in determining the date of a general election.
The introduction of a bill of rights enshrining individual freedom has 72
per cent support, and 60 per cent believe government power is too
centralised.
While majority government is preferred on balance (49 per cent to 45 per
cent), half the public would like to see more co-operation between the
parties.
A devolved assembly is the most popular option among Scottish voters, with
majority support for legislation to establish one in the event of the
Conservative party continuing to hold on to power through the seats won in
England and Wales.
Only 50 per cent of voters know the name of their constituency MP, and only
a third are aware if their constituency comes within the category of a
marginal seat.
Opinion is almost equally divided over political contributions by trade
unions (46 per cent want them banned while 43 per cent do not), and
political contributions by companies (44 per cent want them banned and 45
per cent do not).
Eleven to one favour a Freedom of Information Act (77 per cent for and 7 per
cent against).
Mori interviewed 1,547 adults between March 7 and March 25 in 180
constituencies.
The full State of the Nation computer analysis from Mori costs Pounds 75,
computer disc Pounds 40 and summary Pounds 10.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
