<HEADLINE>
FT  25 APR 91 / Parliament and Politics: Rules on takeovers attacked - Trade
and Industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR JOHN Clark, former chief executive of Plessey the UK electronics group,
yesterday attacked UK takeover regulations, arguing bidders should be
required to exercise due diligence and that shareholders' interests should
not be the sole determinant of a bid.
'I do not believe self-regulation is working or can work,' he said,
addressing the trade and industry select committee on government takeover
and merger policy. 'There should be criteria that can overrule the perceived
best interests of shareholders,' he said.
Sir John argued that due diligence performed by companies in bid situations
should include establishing genuine synergy and mutual benefit, showing that
employee benefits can be enhanced and illustrating that extra monies would
be available for R&amp;D and marketing.
Referring to Plessey's Pounds 2bn takeover by GEC and Siemens in 1989, Sir
John said that 35 fund managers 'who did not know one end of a factory from
another' were the sole arbiters of the company's demise.
He described it as 'utterly absurd' that ownership of UK companies was
largely concentrated among 'a handful of institutions.' This 'cannot be
perceived to be in the public interest,' he said.
He agreed that a central registry of undertakings given by prospective
buyers during the course of bids should be established. Cadbury Schweppes,
the UK confectionery and soft drinks group, told the same committee that it
supports lowering the bid threshold for mandatory bids to 20 per cent from
29.9 per cent at present.
</TEXT>
