<TEXT>
TWO of the three largest US airlines were yesterday awarded new route
authorities between the US and Manchester Airport. At the same time
NorthWest Airlines has been given approval to fly non-stop between Detroit
and London while Virgin Atlantic Airways yesterday received clearance to
start services from Heathrow to New York, Los Angeles and Tokyo.
The US Department of Transportation said it had awarded a New York to
Manchester route authority to American Airlines, and given a service between
Atlanta and Manchester to Delta.
It also awarded a back-up authority for the Delta route to USAir, one of the
middle-ranking US carrier, to provide a service between Pittsburgh and
Manchester.
The department also granted NorthWest Airlines' request to reconsider its
application to fly non-stop between Detroit and London. The airline was
given emergency approval by the US authorities to operate the route until
May 22.
Mr Richard Branson's Virgin Atlantic Airways yesterday received clearance to
start services from London's Heathrow airport to New York, Los Angeles and
Tokyo from July 1.
The date was earlier than expected.
Virgin has fought to be able to fly from Heathrow in competition with
British Airways and the big US carriers.
