<HEADLINE>
FT  25 APR 91 / Trustees win backing for pensions test case
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ERIC SHORT, Pensions Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government has agreed in principle to provide financial backing for
pension scheme trustees in a test case on pensions equality.
It is hoped that the test case, involving the Coloroll Group Pension
Schemes, will resolve ambiguities arising from a European Court judgment
last year. That ruled that benefits paid from occupational pension schemes
counted as pay under Article 119 of the Treaty of Rome and therefore had to
be equal for men and women.
However, the judgment - in the Barber v Guardian Royal Exchange case -
stated that to avoid upsetting the financial balance of schemes, it would
only apply to pension entitlements arising after May 17 1990 - the date of
the judgment.
The confusion arose over whether that related only to the benefits secured
by contributions made after May 17, or to the date when the pension payments
started, or to all pension payments after May 17.
It is intended to bring the case before the High Court within weeks and have
it referred to the European Court within 18 months. A favourable
interpretation could mean minimal initial cost to pensions schemes, but the
cost rises to about Pounds 30bn on the most unfavourable interpretation.
Coloroll Group went into administrative receivership a few weeks after the
judgment.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
