<HEADLINE>
FT  25 APR 91 / EEF and CBI in talks on merger
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL, Business Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE CONFEDERATION of British Industry and the Engineering Employers'
Federation are in talks that might end in the two organisations' merging to
provide a unified voice for the manufacturing sector.
The two bodies said yesterday that they had agreed over the 'absolutely
essential' need for manufacturing industry to have a single, powerful
representative organisation to promote its interests.
The CBI, which was formed in 1965, represents more than 250,000 businesses
employing about half the nation's workforce. Members include most of the 100
largest companies, along with 150 trade association and employers'
organisations.
More than 5,000 businesses are represented by the EEF, the UK's largest
single-industry representative organisation.
Mr Peter Brighton, EEF director-general, said: 'Britain has a unique public
lack of recognition of the importance of engineering and manufacturing
industry to the health of the overall economy.'
Neither party would predict the outcome of a joint working party of senior
officials, which is due to report in the autumn. Mr John Banham, CBI
director-general, said that whatever body emerged, it would be within the
'overall umbrella' of his organisation.
The move, which will replicate recent initiatives among trade unions to
create stronger representative organisations, was originated by the EEF. The
federation's role has been diminished since the end, two years ago, of its
role in national negotiations on minimum pay and conditions.
Mr David Lees, EEF president, said both organisations recognised that
neither the CBI nor the EEF in their present forms could resolve the
difficulties facing manufacturing industry.
The decision to establish a working party was endorsed yesterday by the CBI
Council. Sir Brian Corby, CBI president, said a joint organisation would
improve the effectiveness with which the interests of manufacturers were
represented in Westminster, Whitehall and Brussels.
</TEXT>
