<HEADLINE>
FT  25 APR 91 / PowerGen to close two plants
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
POWERGEN, the UK electricity generator, yesterday announced the closure of
two power stations with the loss of 440 jobs. The company said the stations
were 'inefficient and increasingly unprofitable'.
The 33-year-old Ferrybridge B station in West Yorkshire and the 34-year-old
Hams Hall C station in Warwickshire are due to be shut in November next year
and their output taken on by new installations under construction.
PowerGen has emphasised that replacing coal-fired power stations with
gas-powered plants is a significant part of the company's efficiency drive.
News of the closures follows PowerGen's announcement on Tuesday that it had
awarded the contract for construction of its Pounds 290m gas-powered station
in Hertfordshire to Siemens, the electronic and electrical equipment
supplier. That plant is due to start up in 1994.
In addition, the company's 900MW Killingholme gas-fired station is due to
start up in October next year.
PowerGen said staff levels at the two stations it is closing will start to
be run down from April next year. Some workers will be offered jobs
elsewhere in the company, and other jobs will be lost through natural
wastage and voluntary redundancy.
Mr Malcolm Edwards, commercial director of British Coal, warned against
increasing the UK's energy bill by a rising reliance on imported fuel. Mr
Edwards said that if the short-term view of power station fuel requirements
persisted, it might result in a big rundown in the industry.' Only British
Coal will sign a long contract for a large supply of fuel with prices in
sterling and guaranteed to stay within the UK retail prices index.'
Power workers vote on offer, Page 12
