<HEADLINE>
FT  25 APR 91 / IMF World Economic Outlook: Sluggishness of developing
regions seen as likely to continue
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEPHEN FIDLER, Euromarkets Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE developing economies of eastern Europe, Latin America and the Middle
East contracted last year, and the decline is expected to continue this year
in eastern Europe and the Middle East, according to the International
Monetary Fund.
Its World Economic Outlook suggests overall growth in gross domestic product
in developing countries fell to 0.6 per cent last year, from 3.1 per cent in
1989. It is projected at 0.8 per cent this year, rising to 3.4 per cent next
year.
The IMF estimates the debt of all developing countries rose nearly 6 per
cent in 1990 to Dollars 1,306bn. New borrowing of Dollars 50bn and valuation
changes due to the dollar's fall (Dollars 51bn) more than offset the fall in
debt (Dollars 29bn) due to various operations to reduce the debt of
developing countries.
The amount of debt owed by problem debtor countries to commercial banks is
set to fall to Dollars 257bn in 1992, from Dollars 311bn in 1990, reflecting
both debt reduction deals and net repayments. By 1992, the share of official
debt to these countries will have grown to 52 per cent in 1992 from 47 per
cent in 1990.
Debt reduction operations will contribute to a big drop in debt-GDP ratios
in problem debtor countries.
Among 15 heavily indebted countries, this ratio will fall 7 1/2 percentage
points to 30 per cent in 1992. Debt service ratios will show a temporary
rise this year, however.
The Middle East: Output is estimated to have shrunk by 1.5 per cent last
year, reflecting the sharp contraction of the economies of Kuwait, Iraq and
Jordan.
Total regional output is estimated to decline by a further 3.3 per cent this
year, before recovering in 1992 when 8.5 per cent growth is expected, mainly
because of reconstruction in Kuwait and Iraq.
The combined balance of payments surplus of the Middle East countries is
estimated to have shifted from near balance in 1989 to a surplus of Dollars
14bn last year, mainly because of the rise in oil prices.
It will shift dramatically to deficit of Dollars 50bn this year and Dollars
25bn next, mainly because of economic reconstruction costs.
Latin America: Output declined by 1 per cent last year, compared with a
modest 1.5 per cent rise the year before. Some of the decline was due to
transitional economic adjustments, rather than destabilising macroeconomic
policies - the primary factor in previous years.
If significant delays or slippages in reform programmes are avoided, growth
should resume this year, at about 1 per cent, and reach 3.3 per cent next
year.
Asia: Growth slipped to 5.3 per cent last year in Asian developing
economies, from 5.5 per cent in 1989.
It is expected to remain about 5 per cent this year and next - three
percentage points below the average growth rate for 1983-89. The Gulf war
cost the oil-importing debtor countries of the region almost  1/2 per cent
of GDP last year, with the countries hurt by a loss of remittances.
Africa: The rise in the price of oil and a drop in the price of other
commodities depressed growth in Africa in 1990. Gross domestic product
growth should be little changed at about 2 per cent this year but pick up to
4.8 per cent in 1992. Little progress, though, is seen at alleviating
poverty, and GDP levels per capita are expected to remain at the level of 20
years ago.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 6
</PAGE>
