<HEADLINE>
FT  25 APR 91 / Baker condemns Israel over settlements
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY WALKER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CAIRO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A FRUSTRATED US secretary of state, Mr James Baker, yesterday sharply
criticised Israel over new settlements in the occupied territories amid
signs that his peace shuttle may be faltering.
Speaking to reporters in Damascus after marathon talks with President Hafez
al-Assad, Mr Baker said he was 'very disappointed to learn .. that there is
yet another new settlement established in the (Israeli) occupied
territories'.
'That points up vividly that it is easier to obstruct peace than to promote
it,' he added, in a departure from his previous muted approach to the vexed
settlement issue during his current Middle East tour - his third in six
weeks.
Mr Baker, who arrived in the Soviet Union last night for a meeting with his
Soviet counterpart, spent nine and a half hours with Mr Assad on Tuesday in
talks that reportedly bogged down on UN involvement in a proposed regional
peace conference.
Mr Farouk al-Shara, Syria's foreign minister, who was sitting beside Mr
Baker at yesterday's press conference, said 'the Syrian position vis-a-vis
this point is very clear. The UN should play an important role in this
conference.'
Damascus also wants the conference to have European Community involvement
and to be given the authority to oversee the implementation of decisions
reached.
As Mr Baker prepared for today's meeting with Mr Alexander Bessmertnykh, the
Soviet foreign minister, in a Caucasus resort, it was clear that his peace
shuttle was in trouble.
In his efforts to coax all parties to the dispute to accept the need to
begin talking, he is battling decades of suspicion and prejudice. He is also
obliged to deal with an Israel deeply divided on the international
community's central demand - that agreement be based on exchanging 'land for
peace' in the occupied territories.
