FT  25 APR 91 / Japanese police raid offices of Itoman
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEFAN WAGSTYL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
JAPANESE police and public prosecutors investigating dubious art and
property deals at Itoman, a large but debt-ridden trading company, yesterday
raided 48 homes and offices across the country.
Officials carried away boxes of documents as part of the investigation into
the suspect transactions.
The investigation followed legal complaints made by Itoman, a trading
company based in Osaka, which alleged that paintings were sold to it at
prices well above the market price, a spokesman for the Osaka police and the
Osaka District Prosecutor's Office said.
The Itoman affair has gripped popular imagination in Japan because - to the
disgust of many ordinary Japanese - the company was at the forefront of
speculating in the property boom of the late 1980s.
When it emerged last year that Itoman was in financial trouble servicing a
Y1,300bn (Pounds 5.5bn) debt, Mr Yoshihiko Kawamura, the company president,
resigned, as did the chairman of Sumitomo Bank, Itoman's main bank.
The prosecutor's office is concentrating its investigation on the purchase
for Y55.7bn of valuable paintings, including a Renoir and a Chagall, which
Itoman says were sold to it at two or three times the market price.
