<HEADLINE>
FT  25 APR 91 / Kurdish rebels claim autonomy agreement with Iraq
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
AN IRAQI rebel leader said yesterday that President Saddam Hussein had
agreed to grant a measure of autonomy to the Kurds, raising the prospect of
a negotiated end to the disaster that has forced more than 2m Kurds to flee
their homes in northern Iraq, write our foreign staff.
Mr Jalal Talabani, leader of the Patriotic Union of Kurdistan, announced the
deal 'in principle' after talks with the Iraqi president.
Shortly before the announcement, Mr Abdul Amir Al-Anbari, Iraq's UN
ambassador, said it was his 'impression' an autonomous state might result
from the talks. Asked how far Baghdad was prepared to go towards Kurdish
autonomy, he said: 'They seem to be going all the way.'
Mr Talabani immediately appealed to thousands of refugee Kurdish families
who fled towards Iran and Turkey after a failed uprising to return to their
homes in northern Iraq.
Reaction from Washington and London was cautious. Officials said they had no
confirmation a deal had been signed. One US official said he hoped any deal
'would help facilitate the sense of security for people to return to their
homes', but the US was 'sceptical' because Saddam had previously broken
verbal promises.
Mr Talabani said the deal covered implementation of a March 11 1970 autonomy
agreement between the Kurds, who form 20 per cent of Iraq's population, and
the central government, he added. Negotiations with the authorities in
Baghdad would be resumed on Sunday to flesh out the agreement.
It remains to be seen if Mr Saddam will accept Kurdish demands for a
genuinely autonomous region within a democratic Iraq, for control of oil
revenue from Kurdish areas and for international guarantees to bolster any
agreement that is signed.
Both sides however need a deal. Mr Saddam's army has been weakened by the
Gulf war and he would not be able to use chemical weapons against the Kurds
without angering the international community.
The Kurdish guerrillas are still a force to be reckoned with in the
mountains, but they face an uphill task if nearly 2m refugees - half the
Kurds of Iraq - do not return to their homes.
Kurdish camps Page 4
</TEXT>
