<HEADLINE>
FT  25 APR 91 / GEC Avionics wins Pounds 300m stealth jet computer order
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ORDERS WORTH more than Pounds 300m to supply flight computers and cockpit
display equipment for the next generation of US stealth fighter aircraft
will be announced today by GEC Avionics.
The deal will make the company the only large British supplier for the new
US Advanced Tactical Fighter (ATF) to be built by a consortium including
Lockheed, Boeing and General Dynamics, which was selected by the US Pentagon
on Tuesday.
It also comes on the heels of another contract announced yesterday by GEC
Avionics, which is the aerospace subsidiary of the General Electric Company.
That contract is to supply the primary flight computer system for Boeing's
new wide-bodied commercial airliner, the 777.
Mr Brian Tucker, GEC Avionics managing director, said the potential value of
the combined ATF and Boeing 777 contracts was more than Pounds 500m over 15
years. He added that the orders were initially worth Pounds 60m-Pounds 70m
for the fighter work and more than Pounds 45m for the Boeing 777.
Boeing has so far received launch orders for the 777 from United Airlines
and All Nippon Airways.
The US is planning to commission 650 ATFs, expected to cost Dollars 65bn
(Pounds 38bn) over the next two decades, which would make it the largest
ever aerospace contract.
'The ATF deal places us on both the next generation US tactical fighter
programme and the European Fighter Aircraft (EFA) programme,' Mr Tucker
said.
The UK company has been contracted to supply display and flight control
systems for the EFA and has prime responsibility for the European
three-nation Tornado military aircraft flight control system.
It also supplies computer systems for the European Airbus commercial
aircraft programme.
GEC-Avionics, which is based at Rochester, Kent, where it employs 5000
people, will develop and supply the ATF's pilot's head-up display system,
the pilot's side stick controller and the vehicle management system which
includes the computer fly-by-wire flight controls, hydraulics and
environmental control.
GEC Avionics has become the world's largest supplier of head up display
systems, which enable pilots to see at eye level all their flight manoeuvres
and weapon aiming.
Mr Tucker said the US, the world's biggest aerospace market, now accounted
for about 60 per cent of his company's exports.
Two other British companies, Smiths Industries and Hawker Siddeley, have won
this month substantial orders to supply components for the new Boeing 777.
</TEXT>
