without reducing its holding in Nine, but recently reported an interim loss
of ADollars 90m.
Mr Colin Henson, an ACIL director, said the proceeds of the sale of Nine
Network shares would be used for 'internal funding requirements,' but
declined to give details.
He said there were no plans to dispose of the rest of ACIL's holding in the
Nine Network, which was regarded as 'a long-term investment'.
Shares in the Nine Network have doubled in value since the company was
acquired eight months ago by Consolidated Press Holdings (Conspress), Mr
Packer's privately-owned master company.
The shares closed 2 cents higher on the day at 58 cents on the Australian
Stock Exchange yesterday. ACIL shares closed 1 cent higher at 22 cents.
Conspress, which has a controlling 38.8 per cent stake in Nine Network, has
also given an undertaking to the stock exchange that it has no plans to
reduce its holding.
