<HEADLINE>
FT  25 APR 91 / International Company News: Black &amp; Decker earnings halved
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BLACK &amp; DECKER, the home appliances and power tools maker, saw its
first-quarter earnings halved, but it hoped that an economic revival and low
retailer inventories would boost profits later this year, writes Bernard
Simon.
Net earnings tumbled to Dollars 4.1m, or 7 cents a share, from Dollars 10m,
or 17 cents, a year earlier. Revenues rose by 8 per cent to Dollars 1.1bn,
thanks to the inclusion of information systems business acquired as part of
the 1989 purchase of Emhart Corp. Product sales dipped by 7 per cent.
Financing costs fell by 9 per cent to Dollars 78.5m, reflecting lower
interest rates.
The company said business conditions remained difficult in the US, the UK,
Canada, Brazil and Australia. Temporary plant closures are squeezing
margins, but are expected to bolster cash flow.
</TEXT>
