FT  25 APR 91 / International Company News: Saudi investor lifts Chase stake
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN investment group controlled by Mr Suliman Olayan, the billionaire Saudi
financier, has increased its holding in Chase Manhattan Bank from about 4.2
per cent to about 5.2 per cent, writes Karen Zagor.
The Dollars 159m stake in Chase, the second biggest US commercial banking
group, is held by Crescent Diversified, a subsidiary of Mr Olayan's US
investment arm Olayan Group. The investment comes two months after Saudi
Prince Alwaleed Bin Talel bought Dollars 590m of convertible stock in
Citicorp.
Unlike Prince Alwaleed, who had been a private customer of Citicorp for
about 10 years but only started buying Citicorp shares on the open market
last year, the Olayan Group has invested in Chase for many years.
In a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission, Crescent said it
bought 1.2m shares between March 1 and April 15 at prices ranging from
Dollars 14.37 to Dollars 20.
The Olayan Group, founded by Mr Olayan in 1947, holds stakes in JP Morgan,
First Chicago and Transamerica, First Chicago.
